<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Births Than Deaths in EU in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 23 (Xinhua) -- More babies were born and
fewer people died in the European Union in 1997, contributing to a
population growth of 0.1 percent, Eurostat reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The EU's statistical agency said that births rose to 4,061,500
from 4,045,800 in 1996 while in 1995 they reached a post-war low
of 4,001,800.
</P>
<P>
Deaths are estimated to have fallen from 3,732,700 in 1996 to
3,721,400 last year.
</P>
<P>
Eurostat concluded that the difference in births and deaths
resulted in a probable rise in EU natural population of 340,100 or
0.1 percent growth in total population.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 rise was 313,100.
</P>
<P>
But Eurostat predicted that after the year 2000 there would be
another decrease in births as the large number of women born in
the mid-1960s "baby-boom" move out of the peak childbearing ages
and are replaced by the smaller number of women born between 1965
and 1975.
</P>
<P>
Despite the EU-wide increase of births, half of the European
Union member states saw a decline in births in 1997 compared with
1996.
</P>
<P>
Austria, Sweden, Greece, Finland, Luxembourg, France, Belgium
and Spain all registered decreases in populations with birth rates
dropping by 5.2 percent, 4.4 percent, 3.3 percent, 2 percent, 1.6
percent, 1.2 percent, 0.4 percent and 0.2 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Ireland led the increase of births with 7.4 percent, followed by
Austria at 5.2 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
