</P>
<P>
-- Senior Clinton Administration officials, cautioning that
deeds and not words are required to resolve the crisis with Iraq,
said Sunday that they would withhold judgement on the agreement
announced in Baghdad by the United Nations Secretary General, Kofi
Annan, until he returns to give them a detailed briefing.
</P>
<P>
-- Tobacco industry documents, some released recently, strongly
suggest that the R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Company altered nicotine
delivery to smokers, apparently believing that doing so would
increase the "kick" of its Winston brand and make it more
competitive.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Against a backdrop of threatened U.S. airstrike, U.N.
Secretary General Kofi Annan Sunday night reached an agreement
with senior Baghdad officials that he believes could end the
crisis over U.N. inspections of suspected Iraqi weapons sites, his
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
-- For years, the streets of Washington have been a moonscape
of potholes. But now all 4,000 of them are supposed to be patched
by summer's end, and steamrollers are laying down miles of fresh
asphalt.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Affirmative-action programs face new challenges in
Washington state, where a ban on racial or gender preferences will
be on the the November ballot.
</P>
<P>
USA Today:
</P>
<P>
-- The government's case against two men accused of possessing
the deadly toxin seems to be weakening. But prosecutors and the
FBI aren't saying that they made a mistake.  
</P>
