<HEADLINE> Iran Says No Problem to Repay Foreign Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Governor of the Central Bank of
Iran (CBI) Mohsen Nourbakhsh announced Monday that Iran would not
face any problem to repay its foreign commitments despite of a
reduction of its oil revenue.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, Nourbakhsh said that Iran
would repay all of its commitments on time and without any delay.
</P>
<P>
He put the country's total foreign commitments at 26.4 billion
U.S. dollars, including 14.1 billion dollars foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
He rejected the reports that Iran might face another economic
crisis like that during 1993-1995 when it was forced to reschedule
its foreign arrears.
</P>
<P>
Economic experts have predicted a financial problem for the
country after its oil incomes sharply reduced following the fall
of oil prices during the past year. Some said that Tehran would
be forced to reschedule the payment of its foreign debts again.
</P>
<P>
Nourbakhsh said that the country's oil revenue during the 11
months of the current Iranian fiscal year (to end on March 21)
stood at 14.3 billion dollars with the average price at 15.7
dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
Iran earned 18.5 billion dollars in 1996 when oil price was as
high as 19 dollars per barrel and it expected 17.7 billion
dollars oil revenues in the current Iranian year based on an
average price of 17.5 dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
Prices for Iranian oil dropped from 19 dollars per barrel in
1996 to around 13 dollars at present.
</P>
<P>
The reduction of oil revenue has caused the country to face a
budget deficit of 6,000 billion rials (about 3.4 billion dollars)
Nourbakhsh said, adding that the CBI has started to sell bonds to
make up the budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
He agreed that the country would also face budget deficit in
the coming fiscal year if oil price remains at present level and
the government would be forced to make some revision to the
budget.
</P>
<P>
Nourbakhsh said Iran enjoyed a 3 percent growth rate for gross
domestic products (GDP) in the current Iranian year while the
figure was 4.2 percent last Iranian year.
</P>
<P>
He said that the country could keep the GDP growth rate at
3 percent in the coming Iranian year despite of the present
stagnation in oil market, adding that the country's industrial
sector had a drastic growth during the past years and its growth
rate stood at 6 percent in the current year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
