<HEADLINE> Clinton Offers No Comment on Annan's Deal With Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 23 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton
Monday did not as had been expected make any comment on U.N.
Secretary General Kofi Annan's agreement with Iraqi officials over
weapons inspection.
</P>
<P>
He only said at a gathering of state governors at the White
House that he had spoken to Annan and British Prime Minister Tony
Blair about the agreement.
</P>
<P>
"I've been working on the situation in Iraq.... Last night just
before dinner I spoke with Secretary General Kofi Annan and I have
called Prime Minister Blair this morning. We had a long talk about
the situation."
</P>
<P>
He said he would speak to French President Jacques Chirac and
Russian President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
"That's all I have to say now," he concluded.
</P>
<P>
The United States wants an agreement which gives the U.N.
weapons inspectors free access to all the sites they want to
visit, without the time limits Iraq has tried to impose. 
</P>
</TEXT>
