<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Stand-By Credit for Cape Verde </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 23 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) Monday approved a 14-month stand-by credit for Cape
Verde equivalent to some 2.8 million U.S. dollars to back the
government's 1998 economic program.
</P>
<P>
However, the Cape Verde authorities have indicated their
intention not to draw on the credit.
</P>
<P>
The macroeconomic program is designed to reach real GDP growth
of 4 percent in 1998, as compared with 3 percent in 1997, and an
average inflation rate of 3.5 percent in 1998, as against 8.9
percent last year. The external current account balance, excluding
transfers, is targeted at a deficit of 15.7 percent of GDP in 1998
as compared with a deficit of 16.4 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The most important content of the program is a tightening of
fiscal policy to reduce the overall fiscal deficit to 8.7 percent
of GDP in 1998 from 15.1 percent in 1997. The deficit is to be
entirely financed by concessional foreign borrowing.
</P>
<P>
Cape Verde joined the IMF in November 1978. Its quota is about
9.4 million dollars equivalent. The country has no outstanding use
of IMF financing so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
