<HEADLINE> Pak PM Expresses Satisfaction with UN-Iraq Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif has expressed satisfaction with the just-concluded
accord between the U.N. and the Iraqi government pertaining to the
standoff on the issue of weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
In a letter addressed to U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan,
Sharif expressed the hope that with this agreement the prospect of
military action would completely be averted.
</P>
<P>
According to the Associated Press of Pakistan, Sharif said in
his letter that "if approved by the (U.N.) Security Council this
agreement would represent the success of diplomacy rather than the
use of force."
</P>
<P>
Sharif observed that a key element in the accord is "ensuring
respect of Security Council resolutions governing the inspection
regime in Iraq."
</P>
<P>
Referring to his letter of February 21 to the U.N. secretary
general, Sharif stressed that "this demonstrates the importance of
implementing all Security Council resolutions in letter and spirit
whether they pertain to Iraq, Kashmir, Lebanon, Palestine or any
other issue for maintaining global and regional peace and
security."
</P>
<P>
The prime minister has also welcomed the Security Council's
decision of February 20 to increase the oil-for-food program for
Iraq under which it would be able to sell 5.2 billion U.S.
dollars worth of oil every six months.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that this will contribute to alleviating
the sufferings of the Iraqi people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
