<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Epidemic Diseases Under Control in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Health Minister
Jackson Kalweo Monday said that Rift Valley fever in the
Northeastern province had been "successfully contained" and
cholera and malaria were also "on the decline" in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Rift Valley fever first emerged in the province two months
ago and the Kenyan Health Ministry issued an alert earlier this
month to Nairobi residents over possible outbreak of the fever in
the capital as the killer disease had been making a steady spread
westward.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held here Monday, the minister assured
Kenyans that the fast killing fever had been brought under
control.
</P>
<P>
He said that a total of 846 Kenyans died of cholera since last
June, adding that it is, therefore, imperative that public health
education on hygiene should be continued to avert possible
recurrence of cholera.
</P>
<P>
In the case of malaria, the minister said, the worst affected
districts in the east African country include Kisii, Nyamira,
Kericho, West Pokot, Samburu, Uasin Gishu, Kakamega, Nandi, Trans
Nzola, Wajir, Garissa, Mandera and Trans Mara.
</P>
<P>
Kalweo pointed out that a team of experts was sent to the
worst hit areas to assess the situation and a task force had been
set up to deal with the malaria menace since the disease was
expected to persist until July in the wake of the onset of the
long rains in March.
</P>
<P>
Malaria epidemic usually occurs during the months of May-July
after the long rains. However, the disease occurred earlier than
expected due to the unusual prolonged rains caused by the El Nino
weather phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan Health Ministry has launched a social mobilization
campaign, recommending immediate clearing of bushes around houses
and draining of stagnant water in pools all over the country to
eradicate all possible mosquito breeding sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
