<HEADLINE> Protection of Mt Uluguru Urged in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Environmentalists have
urged the Morogoro municipality in southern Tanzania to curb
massive felling of trees on the Uluguru Mountains, Daily News
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Environmental experts and representatives who have been
attending a seminar on biogas technology in Morogoro, said wanton
destruction of forests on the mountains threaten to deplete the
water source for the Ruvu River, a lifeline for Dar es Salaam and
adjacent areas.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 participants from local non-government
organizations (NGOs) called on the municipal authorities to work
out the strategies to protect the ecosystem of the mountain with
the Sokoine University of Agriculture, for the benefit of future
generations.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was organized by a local NGO in Morogoro, the
Foundation for Sustainable Rural Development (SURUDE) and was
sponsored by the Africa 2000 Network, a UNDP-financed program.
</P>
<P>
Heavy use of wood for fuel, overgrazing and fires have made
the country lose 300,000 and 400,000 hectares of forests each
year.
</P>
<P>
The workshop has called on Africa 2000 Network in
collaboration with SURUDE to promote the technology of using
tubular plastic biodigesters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
