<HEADLINE> Jordan Exerts Efforts to Avert Strike on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, February 23 (Xinhua) -- A senior Jordanian official said
Monday that Jordan had exerted efforts to help prevent a U.S.
military strike against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with official Jordan Television Station, Deputy
Prime Minister for Development and Minister of Foreign Affairs
Jawad Anani said that Jordan's endeavors were made at a time when
opportunities of averting a military strike seemed "extremely
slight."
</P>
<P>
"Jordan's strategy and foreign policy in dealing with the
crisis focused on one goal which is to avert a military strike on
Iraq," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to avoid the possible U.S. military actions against
Iraq, Jordanian officials held talks with Iraqi Foreign Minister
Mohammed Saeed Al-Sahhaf to discuss the Iraq-U.N. crisis over arms
inspection, he said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan also held consultations and contacts with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak and Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid in this regard, Anani added.
</P>
<P>
United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan Monday made a
telephone call to King Hussein of Jordan to commend Jordan's role
in averting U.S. military strike on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Annan expressed U.N.'s appreciation for Jordan's "clear and
active stand" which contributed to defusing the crisis and
averting a military option.
</P>
<P>
During the crisis triggered by Iraq's refusal to allow
U.N. arms inspectors to full access to Iraq's sites suspected of
hiding banned weapons, Jordan had exerted efforts at national,
bilateral, regional and international levels to help prevent the
United States from staging military strike on Iraq to force it to
fully comply with U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The Untied States has threatened to resort to force if
diplomacy fails to solve the confrontation with Iraq
peacefully.


23/02/98 16:28 GMT

