<HEADLINE> Massive Car Bomb Blast in Northern Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 23 (Xinhua) -- A car bomb exploded in the
center of Portadown in Northern Ireland Monday after several
warning calls, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Army bomb experts were investigating the area, which was
evacuated before the blast occurred. There were no casualties.
</P>
<P>
The explosion came as the peace talks resumed in Belfast Monday
without Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish Republican Army
(IRA), which was expelled last Friday for the IRA's alleged
involvement in two murders early this month.
</P>
<P>
Kenneth Twyble, mayor of Portadown, said people were "shocked
and stunned" by the attack, which damaged more than 12 buildings
in a narrow street.
</P>
<P>
Those responsible for the blast "do not want peace" in Northern
Ireland, he added.
</P>
<P>
Police said the bomb, planted in a car parked 200 meters from a
police station, caused extensive damage to banks and other
businesses in this town about 45 km southwest of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
No group has claimed responsibility for the attack.
</P>
<P>
Two bombs were planted in Northern Ireland at the weekend. One
wrecked a police station and wounded 11 people in the town of
Moira, while the other under a taxi in Belfast was destroyed by
police in a controlled explosion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
