<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Ruling Party Has No Power Struggle: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 23 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Lesotho
Congress for Democracy (LDC) on Monday denied that there was a
power struggle between the party's two most senior leaders.
</P>
<P>
However, it confirmed there was a debate about the separation
of party ledership and premiership of the country.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted unidentified
Lesotho officials as reporting that the tussle is between newly
elected LCD leader Pakalitha Mosisili and his deputy Kelebone
Maope.
</P>
<P>
Mosisili is Lesotho's current deputy prime minister while
Maope is foreign minister. They were elected to their new party
positions at a special congress on Saturday following Prime
Minister Ntsu Mokhehle's recent resignation from the LCD
leadership due to poor health and old-age.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle also announced that he would not be available for
re-election as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Mosisili had been Mokhehle's deputy since they broke away from
the former ruling Basutoland Congress Party and formed the LCD in
June last year.
</P>
<P>
Reports of simmering tension between Mosisili and Maope
emerged during the weekend congress, and this resulted in a
deadlock over who should succeed 79-year-old Mokhehle.
</P>
<P>
A compromise was later reached and Mosisili won, but the
question of the separation of the roles arose.
</P>
<P>
One group wants Maope to be nominated for the premiership of
the country after the May 23 general elections, while another
supports Mosisili's nomination for the post.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Maope group was reportedly arguing that Lesotho is
presently in a transitional phase and they believe there is need
to search for the right person to perform the various political
roles within the party and government.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted a source close to Maope as saying that the foreign
minister was not interested in contesting the premiership, but
would consider any deployment by the party.
</P>
<P>
Tom Thabane, Mokhehle's special advisor and senior LCD member,
said the LCD was democratic, and the party members determine
their leaders' roles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
