<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece: No U.S. Proposal for Non-Aggression Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Greece denied Monday that there
was a definite proposal by the U.S. for the signing of a
non-aggression agreement between Greece and neighboring Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Replying to questions concerning a reported initiative by U.S.
special envoy to Cyprus Richard Holbrooke, Greek government
spokesman Dimitris Reppas told reporters that there was no
specific formula with an explicit content regarding the signing of
a non-aggression accord between the two countries whose relations
have been at odds over decades for differences in the Aegean Sea
and the prolonged Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that although such ideas had been raised for
years, they had not been in the form of official proposals.
</P>
<P>
Greece's policy allowed third parties to understand that Athens
wanted the rules of international law and order to be implemented,
he said, adding that if Turkey declared it would respect these
rules and recognized the jurisdiction of the international court
in the Hague, new conditions for the signing of a non-aggression
pact could be created.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Reppas also described the statements made in Paris
by Turkish President Suleyman Demirel regarding "grey areas" in
the Aegean Sea as a "provocation."
</P>
<P>
Greece has insisted that there is no dispute between the two
countries in the Aegean except the continental shelf, and invited
the neighboring country to refer all its claims in the Aegean to
the international court in the Hague. 
</P>
</TEXT>
