<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Exile President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah of Sierra Leone has sent a special team to Freetown,
capital of Sierra Leone, to assess the situation there for his
return, which is expected to take place this week.
</P>
<P>
The committee, reportedly set up after the collapse of the
military junta about a fortnight ago, is to reassess damages and
look into the security of the state.
</P>
<P>
It may also try to find out who have collaborated with the
military junta which sent the elected government in exile for the
past nine months, according to a British Broadcasting Corporation
report monitored here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report disclosed that there is a list compiled by the
United Nations, which consists of businessmen, several
politicians and other Sierra Leoneans who have actually worked
with the junta.
</P>
<P>
However, the composition of the committee is said to have met
different responses among the Freetown residents,
</P>
<P>
Some people welcome the committee while some other people said
it is not what they have been expecting because nobody in the
committee have stayed in Freetown since the coup last May.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Kabbah met with members of his cabinet and the
parliament in Conakry, capital of Guinea, to discuss his return.
Leaders of west African countries also seem to agree an earlier
comeback of Kabbah than the originally fixed date of April 22.
</P>
