<HEADLINE> Internet Hurts Family Life: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Half of Canadians know someone
who spends so much time surfing the Internet or playing computer
games that it hurts their family life, according to a survey
published Monday.
</P>
<P>
"There is a resonance among many Canadians that the Internet is
helping to create new, virtual communities, and has the potential
to improve family life," the survey said.
</P>
<P>
"But there are also others who see it as impersonal,
dehumanizing and a distraction," it noted.
</P>
<P>
Forty-nine percent of those surveyed said they know people who
spend so much time at home using the Internet and other computer
activities that it is having a negative impact on their family
life.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, some 30 percent of those surveyed said they
strongly disagree with the notion that Internet has had a negative
impact on the quality of people's family life.
</P>
<P>
The survey, done by Ekos Research Associates Inc., interviewed
3,522 Canadians, according to the Globe and Mail newspaper.
</P>
</TEXT>
