<HEADLINE>   Europe-Wide TV Competition Against Racism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Young people in Europe who
want to enter the TV industry can try their luck in a competition
against racism.
</P>
<P>
The competition, open to those aged between 17 and 25 from both
European Union member and associate states, is intended to attract
proposals for a 30-minute anti-racism documentary which are better
than anything produced in the past.
</P>
<P>
The initiative for the television competition was put forward
by the European Multicultural Media Agency in association with
major European broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
Designed to discover new talent with fresh ideas on tackling
the issue of the European Year Against Racism, the competition is
open to all young Europeans, particularly those from ethnic
minorities, European Commission officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
They added that the competition will put TV center stage in
combatting racial injustice.
</P>
<P>
A jury including representatives of five European broadcasters
and the European Commission will select four production proposals
to receive special production awards in April this year.
</P>
<P>
Production will take place between May and August and
broadcasting is scheduled for later this year.
</P>
<P>
It is planned to present adaptations of these productions as
educational packs for secondary schools or media study courses.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission designated the year 1998 as the
European Year Against Racism and a variety of activities were held
to arouse public awareness against the problem.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey conducted by the commission, the executive body
of the 15-nation European Union, revealed that one third of the
respondents to the survey claimed to be still "quite" racist in
mind at least. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
