<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Foreign Ministers Welcome UN-Iraq Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 23 (Xinhua) -- European Union foreign
ministers welcomed Monday the announcement that the United Nations
secretary-general had signed an agreement with the Iraqi
authorities on a diplomatic solution to the crisis with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Robin Cook, foreign secretary of Britain that is serving the
rotating presidency of the 15-nation union, told a press
conference that the one thing he would add to the foreign minister
council conclusion was that if there had been no pressure, there
would be no deal.
</P>
<P>
When asked to elaborate on the word "pressure," Cook said that
he meant the threat of the use of force.
</P>
<P>
The EU council meeting of foreign ministers noted that the
securing of an agreement was only possible because of the firm
resolve shown by the United Nations and the international
community.
</P>
<P>
The British foreign secretary said that Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein had climbed down from several of his demands in that he
had been restricting U.N. inspectors from tours of his
presidential palaces.
</P>
<P>
"There is no longer a time limit by when the inspectors have to
be out and there is no restriction on the work of inspectors,"
said Cook who was chairing the one-day council meeting of EU
foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
"This represents very good progress but there remain some hard
questions to be asked about the precise nature of the agreement
and there will be hard work to be done to make sure that we are
satisfied that this is an agreement that can achieve our key
objective," he added.
</P>
<P>
Cook said that the key objective was to stop Saddam Hussein
from producing chemical and biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
The council meeting recalled that U.N. inspectors must be able
to resume effective inspections as mandated by the U.N. Security
Council resolutions and Iraq must allow U.N. inspectors
unrestricted and unfettered access to all sites and to carry out
effective inspections.
</P>
<P>
The British foreign secretary said that the council had
expressed concern at the humanitarian situation in Iraq and
appreciated the U.N. Security Council's resolution to more than
double the "oil-for-food" program.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan flew to Baghdad over the
weekend to negotiate the agreement, of which the details are still
not yet known.
</P>
<P>
Cook said that he was waiting for further details about the
agreement after Annan returns to New York and brief the U.N.
Security Council while Foreign Minister Jacques Poos of
Luxembourg, that was the previous rotating president of the
European Union, hoped that the details of the agreement would
allow the U.N. Security Council to accept it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
