<HEADLINE> Kuwait Cautiously Welcomes Iraq-UN Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait cautiously
welcomed Monday the agreement signed by U.N. Secretary General
Kofi Annan and Iraq, but wondered whether the agreement involved
full Iraqi implementation of all U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait Crown Prince and Prime Minister Sheikh Saad Al-Abdulla
Al-Sabah was quoted by Kuwait News Agency (KUNA) as saying that
"the agreement with Iraq needs more studying, we must read what is
between the lines."
</P>
<P>
He also wondered whether the agreement means that "Iraq agreed
to implement all UN resolutions?"
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sheikh
Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah said that Kuwait is "happy for any
agreement signed to spare the region the dangers and at the
same time make Iraq comply with Security Council resolutions.
But we must first see the details of this agreement."
</P>
<P>
Annan signed an agreement with Iraq Monday which was said
to have settled all the major issues in Iraq's dispute with the
United Nations over weapons inspections. But details of the
agreement will be disclosed only after Annan submits it to
the U.N. Security Council Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Sabah said that Kuwait "welcomed the agreement before
knowing its details to avert dangers, but it is premature to
talk about the details."
</P>
<P>
Minister of Information Sheikh Saud Nasser Al-Sabah also
said that Kuwait "cautiously welcomes the agreement between
Annan and Iraq" until all the details are released, according
to the KUNA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
