<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Projects 2.5 Bln Dlr Drop in Farm Exports in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Attributing mainly to the
economic woe in Asia and global competition, the U.S. projected
farm exports for 1998 were lowered by 2.5 billion U.S. dollars,
announced Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture Department estimated this year's export could
reach 56 billion dollars, down from the original forecast of 58.5
billion dollars, which would be 2 percent below 1997 levels and
would be the lowest since the 54.6 billion dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The department also predicted that the country's beef, poultry
and pork production would exceed 1997 levels this year, which
could interpret it into lower meat prices for consumers. It also
said soybean and corn production was on the increase.
</P>
<P>
In an address at the annual agriculture outlook forum, Glickman
said the reduction again demonstrates the need for the
International Monetary Fund bailout and for the United States to
continue opening up markets as alternatives to Asia.
</P>
<P>
Since the department's December export projection, estimates
for corn exports were reduced by 7 million tons, or 11 percent
below 1997. Other sharp reductions were in exports of meat, hides
and skins, and fruit and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the IMF bailout, Glickman said the Agriculture
Department would continue its use of credit guarantees to enable
Asia's troubled economies to buy U.S. farm goods. Already, some
2.1 billion dollars in guarantees have been offered.
</P>
<P>
The soybean crop was forecast at 2.8 billion bushels, with corn
at 9.8 billion bushels. Wheat was expected to drop by 9 percent to
2.3 billion bushels and cotton production to decrease by 7
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
