<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CBI Warns Firms of Millennium Chaos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 23 (Xinhua) -- British companies were urged
Monday to share their experiences of dealing with the millennium
computer date problem by the Confederation of British Industries
(CBI).
</P>
<P>
It is known that supermarket cash tills may not work, car-park
barriers could get stuck, accounting programs could add up to 100
years extra interest to bank accounts and traffic lights may fail
if computers are not fully prepared for the start of the new
century.
</P>
<P>
Peter Agar, CBI's deputy director-general, said that companies
have only 20 months to make sure that their information technology
systems and embedded electronic devices can cope with the
millennium date change.
</P>
<P>
The millennium time-bomb would affect all companies, but there
are common solutions to the problem and companies can learn from
one another, he said.
</P>
<P>
To stimulate companies to act now, the CBI has produced a brief
which outlines what four leading UK companies, Sainsbury, Rover,
GRE and Yorkshire Electricity, have done to get ready for the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
Agar told a businessmen gathering here that companies must
carefully plan their use of time and resources if they are to
check all their electronic equipment and, where necessary, get it
reprogrammed before midnight on December 31, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HSBC Holdings Reports Pre-Tax Profit in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 23 (Xinhua) -- HSBC Holdings plc made a profit
before tax of 4,971 million pounds (7,953 million U.S. dollars) in
1997, an increase of 447 million pounds (715 million dollars), or
10 percent over 1996, John Bond, group chief executive, announced
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Its net interest income of 6,680 million pounds (10,688 million
dollars) was 859 million pounds (1,374 million dollars), or 15
percent higher than 1996.
</P>
<P>
Other operating income of the group, one of the biggest
companies in the world, rose by 912 million pounds (1,456 million
dollars), or 24 percent to 4,679 million pounds (7,486 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Profit attributable to shareholders was 3,355 million pounds
(5,368 million dollars) in 1997, an increase of 8 percent,
according to the announcement.
</P>
<P>
However, the strengthening of sterling during 1997 reduced
growth in attributable profits by 4 percentage points compared to
1996, Bond said.
</P>
<P>
The group's total assets at 31 December 1997 were 286 billion
pounds (458 billion dollars), an increase of 50 billion pounds (80
billion dollars), or 21 percent since year-end 1996. 
</P>
