<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-23 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: Countries Express Satisfaction With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Many countries across the world
welcomed the U.N.-Iraq agreement signed in Baghdad Monday on
peaceful solution to the arms inspections crisis. But the U.S. and
Britain said details of the agreement should be studied.
</P>
<P>
After two-day intensive talks, U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan signed the agreement Monday with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz to solve the crisis over weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
China welcomed the agreement, which it hopes "will drive away
the war cloud over the Gulf region, laying a base for the
settlement of the weapons inspection crisis in a just and
reasonable way by peaceful means."
</P>
<P>
"We highly appreciate and support the diplomatic efforts made
by the U.N. Secretary General on the matter and positively value
the wisdom and flexibility demonstrated by relevant parties to
achieve the result," Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu
Bangzao told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Russia, which has been making intensive efforts to defuse the
Iraq crisis in recent weeks, expressed satisfaction with the
encouraging results made by Iraq and U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin told reporters that the Iraq
crisis has been effectively contained through diplomatic efforts.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Anne Secret-Gazequ said
Annan's trip in Iraq which culminated in reaching the agreement
has taken a big step forward in defusing the crisis.
</P>
<P>
China, Russia and France are the three permanent members of the
U.N. Security Council that are strongly opposed to the use of
force against Iraq. U.S. and Britain, the other two members,
have threatened to resort to force if diplomacy fails.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Minister Robin Cook said on Monday that the
deal looked "encouraging," but would have to be studied closely,
adding that Britain would hear details from Annan when he returns
to brief the U.N. Security Council in New York.
</P>
<P>
U.S. diplomats prepared Monday to analyze details of the
agreement as its forces in the Gulf maintained military readiness.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials emphasized that President Bill Clinton would not
comment in a substantive way until he knows more of the details of
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has not reduced its military presence in the Gulf and
said it will not decide whether to endorse the agreement until
after making a careful study.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
