<HEADLINE> Writethru: Countries Express Satisfaction With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 23 (Xinhua) -- The 22-member Arab League (AL)
has expressed welcome to the agreement. AL Secretary General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid said he hopes the Security Council would "complete
the success" fulfilled by the U.N. chief.
</P>
<P>
Egypt voiced its satisfaction with the agreement and termed it
as "encouraging."
</P>
<P>
"I hope the agreement would serve as the final solution to the
Iraqi crisis so that inspection process would continue according
to the U.N. Security Council resolutions," Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, a neighbor of Iraq, warmly welcomed the positive
outcome achieved by Iraq and the U.N. chief.
</P>
<P>
"Jordan is happy that the crisis has come to an end ... and
appreciates the efforts and positive stands taken by the Iraqi
government and the U.N. Secretary General to achieve a solution
that averts the region from devastating consequences," Jordan's
Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Jawad Anani said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he cautioned that peace-loving people should keep
their vigilance that the danger of an attack on Iraq is still in
place.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Gaza, Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat said he is happy to hear the good news of
the signing of the agreement, which he welcomed and really
appreciated.
</P>
<P>
"It is a very successful step, we appreciate it very much," he
said, calling the agreement as a "good start to achieving real
peace and to avoiding military activity."
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu extended a cautious
welcome to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Israeli Knesset (Parliament) members, he expressed
his belief that the agreement is good news as long as there is no
"complicating details" in it.
</P>
<P>
Iran expressed its pleasure that the agreement will help Iraq
avert a military attack by the United States.
</P>
<P>
Iran is pleased with the positive result of Annan's visit to
Baghdad and hopes that the Iraq crisis will finally be resolved
peacefully, Secretary of Iran's Supreme Council of National
Security Hassan Rowhani told the Tehran Radio.
</P>
<P>
A government spokesman of Saudi Arabia, which refused to allow
the U.S. to use its land for launching attack against Iraq, said
his country is completely satisfied with the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Other Gulf countries, such as Kuwait, Qatar, the United Arab
Emirates, Oman Bahrain, also expressed welcome to the signing of
the deal.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU) cautiously welcomed the deal. At a
meeting of the foreign ministers of the 15-nation union Monday,
the participants agreed to back continuing diplomatic efforts to
solve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Luxembourg Foreign Minister Jacques Poos said he is "very
satisfied" with the deal and expressed the hope that the
U.N. Security Council would accept the details of the deal on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Japan expressed its cautious optimism about the breakthrough.
"I hope things turn out as reported," Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto was quoted as saying by Kyodo news agency.
</P>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard said he is hopeful the
agreement will prevent an attack against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Greece has welcomed the deal. Government spokesman Dimitris
Reppas described the agreement as a "positive development," hoping
the diplomatic process would prove successful and that military
action would be averted.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot government spokesman Manolis Christofides congratulated
Annan on the agreement, saying the deal "constitutes an invaluable
contribution to peace." 
</P>
