<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-23 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Continue Defense Preparation Despite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Israeli leaders ordered
Monday to continue the ongoing defense preparations despite the
agreement reached between U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and
the Iraqi government on weapons inspection.
</P>
<P>
Although there was an apparent sense of relief over the
U.N.-Iraqi agreement that could avert a possible U.S. military
attack on Iraq, Israeli leaders remained cautious if the Iraqi
crisis is over pending the reactions from the U.N. Security
Council, especially from the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after attending a meeting of the Knesset
(Parliament) Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee, Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said he thought the agreement is good
news as long as there's no "complicating details" within it.
</P>
<P>
Noting Israel is living in a new Middle East of missiles,
Netanyahu said Israel's defense preparedness would continue. He
claimed that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein would continue
developing weapons of mass destruction, so it was still too early
to say if the crisis is over.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials widely believed that the U.N.-Iraq deal could
only bring a temporary break in the current crisis, and Saddam
would create new troubles in the future.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after Annan's announcement of reaching an
agreement in Baghdad, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai convened
a meeting of senior security and army officers to reassess the
situation. He ordered the continuation of civil preparedness and
acceleration of acquiring protection equipment from abroad.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, the various gas masks distribution centers around
the country will also continue to be open 24 hours daily,
although the usually long queues have disappeared in most centers
due to the positive news from Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The only thing that has been put on hold is the free
distribution of antibiotics to citizens through the pharmacy
shops, which was originally due to begin late Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the past weeks, Israel has been nervously following the
developments in the Persian Gulf as the military
Iraqi-U.N. standoff continued escalating.
</P>
<P>
A panic was created among the public as the government warned
that Iraq could retaliate U.S. military actions by firing
biological and chemical missiles at Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
