<HEADLINE> Mugabe Wants Dialogue Not Violence to Settle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe has urged Zimbabweans to engage in dialogue as a means of
articulating their grievances and shun a culture of violence
which seemed to be fueled by the labor movement leaders.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe made the appeal at a solidarity rally in Chitungwiza
near Harare Sunday. The president called for the rally following
food riots which rocked the town recently resulting in massive
destruction of property.
</P>
<P>
He said, "we went to war, and you elected your government so
that it can govern in peace. We must, therefore, not be seen to
be fighting among ourselves. There must be a culture of dialogue
and discussion."
</P>
<P>
He said such a spirit had culminated in the unity accord which
brought a halt to the dissident activities in the country.
</P>
<P>
Chitungwiza was one of the towns which was hardest hit when
people went on an orgy of looting and damaged shops during the
food riots last month.
</P>
<P>
Rioting and looting would not provide the solutions, Mugabe
said, urging the trade union leaders to desist from inciting
riots which culminated in wanton thefts and damage to property.
</P>
</TEXT>
