help Iraq's compliance with U.N. resolutions so as to save the
Iraqi people from further suffering," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the past days, his country attached serious
concerns over the efforts by Annan during his visit in Baghdad to
bring about a "peaceful and satisfactory" settlement to the crisis.
And now, he said, Muscat was happy to see such a solution.
</P>
<P>
After rounds of talks, Annan and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz signed the agreement on peacefully resolving the
crisis in Baghdad Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Annan has left Baghdad for New York and will discuss the deal
with the five permanent members of the Security Council Tuesday.
He said he is hopeful that all the permanent members will accept
the deal.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have threatened to launch military strike
against Iraq if Annan's trip to Baghdad, starting from Friday,
failed to persuade Iraq to grant full access to the U.N. arms
inspectors. 
