<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK to Maintain Military Presence in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Britain said Monday that
although the deal reached by United Nations Secretary General Kofi
Annan with Iraq looked encouraging, it would not scale down its
military preparations in the Gulf for now.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook spoke on the BBC radio that
Britain would not comment on the deal until being briefed by Annan
Tuesday, but he added that he hoped very much it was the deal
Britain was looking for.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary George Robertson also said that Britain would
like to know the details of the accord and be absolutely certain
that Iraq would comply with it before removing its military
presence in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
"We will obviously want to look at the detail of whatever deal
has been signed, and we certainly won't be doing anything about
removing our military capability until we are absolutely certain
that Saddam will comply," Robertson told the BBC radio.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a Downing Street spokesman made clear that Britain
had yet to see a text of the agreement with Iraq, and was still
cautious.
</P>
<P>
"Until we are 100 percent sure that this agreement will assure
all our objectives, there can be no question of scaling down
military preparations. Those preparations will go on," he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added that Britain had told its U.N. ambassador
Michael Weston to step up work on a new Security Council
resolution which would give authority for the U.N. to respond
"rapidly and by whatever means are necessary" should Saddam break
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Britain has been standing firmly side by side with the U.S. in
the weeks-long arms inspection crisis with Iraq and has sent an
aircraft carrier and combat aircraft to the Gulf region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
