<HEADLINE> Cyprus Reiterates Right to Deploy Russian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Government spokesman
Manolis Christofides stressed here Monday that Cyprus has every
right to purchase and deploy the Russian S-300 anti-aircraft
missiles in order to strengthen its defenses.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the missiles will be deployed after Autumn
and there is no change in the date of arrival.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting at his daily press briefing on a statement
by a U.S. official carried by a Greek newspaper Sunday that the
U.S. cannot prevent a possible attempt by Turkey to destroy the
missiles.
</P>
<P>
Christofides said the Turkish threats are not new and noted
that the U.S. has objected to the deployment of the missile
system.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government decided last year to purchase
Russian-made S-300 surface-to-air missile system to raise its
defense capability.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has threatened to strike the missiles if they are
deployed on the island.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman cited a statement Sunday by Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides that all the necessary measures have been taken
in case the missiles are attacked.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community have been trying for
decades to reunite the divided island as a bizonal, bicommunal
federal state, but so far no tangible results have been
achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
