<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Hails U.N.-Iraqi Deal on Arms Inspection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Turkey Monday welcomed the
agreement reached by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and the
Iraqi government over weapons inspection which could avert a
military strike on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here, Turkish Foreign Minister
Ismail Cem said that Turkey is satisfied with the U.N.-Iraqi
accord signed by the U.N. chief and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz because it could help defuse the crisis in a peaceful
way.
</P>
<P>
"We are satisfied with the agreement and we are proud of our
minor contribution in that direction," Cem said, referring to the
efforts Turkey had made in finding a diplomatic solution to
the U.S.-Iraqi standoff.
</P>
<P>
He said that what should be done now is to "remove those
political and social factors that cause the crisis step by step."
However, he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
On the role of the newly signed U.N.-Iraqi agreement, Cem
noted that this is not the end of the crisis and more efforts have
to be made for a final settlement.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that he will visit Jordan on
Thursday to exchange views with the kingdom's leadership over the
current situation in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been urging Iraqi President Saddam Hussein to
comply fully with the relevant U.N. Security Council resolutions
in order to avert military confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkish leaders said on many occasions that the
economic sanctions imposed on Iraq seven years ago should be
lifted as early as possible so that the Iraqi people could live a
normal life.
</P>
<P>
The lift of the sanctions imposed on Iraq due to its invasion
of Kuwait in 1990 can not take place unless U.N. weapons
inspectors verify that Iraq has been disarmed weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's refusal to inspectors of free and unfettered access to
all suspected sites triggered off the current crisis. The U.S. and
Britain threatened to launch military strike against Iraq if
diplomacy failed to solve the standoff peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Annan and Aziz signed the agreement Monday morning in Baghdad
which the U.N. chief said will be acceptable to all the members of
the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration, however, reiterated that Iraq must
comply with the U.N. resolutions and said that preparations for
military strikes against Baghdad will not stop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
