<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agency Set Up to Assist Less Advantaged Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 23 (Xinhua) -- A new agency within the
framework of the World Trade Organization (WTO) was inaugurated
here Monday to help less advantaged countries (LACs) integrate
into the new international trade environment.
</P>
<P>
The newly established Agency for International Trade
Information and Cooperation, to be funded by the Swiss federal
government, is aimed at assist LACs to benefit from the
multilateral trading system through a more active participation in
the activities and negotiations of the WTO and other trade-related
international organizations.
</P>
<P>
LACs refer to least developed and other low income countries
including some economies in transition, where the annual income
per capita is less than 1,000 U.S. dollars and the participation
in international trade has not been active traditionally.
</P>
<P>
The assistance that the agency will provide include:
</P>
<P>
-- To define priorities for a delegation which may have only
one person specializing on trade matters and he has a large number
of meetings to cover in several different organizations;
</P>
<P>
-- In a similar situation, to provide summaries and analysis of
lengthy documents on issues on which a LAC may have an interest,
but has not been able to follow in the past;
</P>
<P>
-- To provide information to countries which do not have a
mission in Geneva, and to facilitate interaction with the staff of
the different trade-related organizations;
</P>
<P>
-- To assist Geneva-based diplomats in becoming familiarized
with trade-related issues through a personalized service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
