<HEADLINE> Yeltsin, Clinton Talk on Resolution on Iraq by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
and U.S. President Bill Clinton had a telephone conversation
Monday over the Iraq problem and decided to instruct their foreign
ministers to work out a U.N. Security Council resolution on the
Arab state.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency cited presidential press secretary
Sergei Yastrzhembsky as saying that the two leaders stressed "the
great positive significance of the agreements reached in Baghdad
between Annan and the Iraqi leadership."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said that the Annan-Baghdad understanding may open the
door to the implementation of all U.N. Security Council
resolutions on Iraq and consequently to the complete elimination
of Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said it is impermissible to have a repetition of the
current crisis in Iraq resulting from the suspension of the
operation of U.N. inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said that the agreement signed Monday morning by Annan
and the Iraqi leadership offers a guarantee to prevent new crises.
</P>
<P>
The Russian president attributed the success to the unity of
all permanent members of the U.N. Secruity Council and other
influential members of the world community, saying "we will be
able to avoid serious international crises on a regional as well
as on a global scale in the future."
</P>
<P>
Clinton, meanwhile, said he is aware of the great work done by
Russia to find a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
Yastrzhembsky was also quoted as saying that Yeltsin Monday
sent messages to Clinton, Annan and Chinese Chairman Jiang Zemin,
and on behalf of the Russian leadership praised the results of
Annan's mission to Baghdad and the understandings reached there in
the context of the political settlement of the Iraqi crisis.
</P>
