<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-23 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Opposition Ends Political Ceasefire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Hardly has the Iraq crisis
passed, Israel's opposition Labor Party immediately decided
Monday to end the political ceasefire with the government
observed since early this month.
</P>
<P>
The leading opposition party announced that it would table a
non-confidence motion in the Knesset (Parliament) next Monday
against the Likud-led government over its poor handling of the
Iraq crisis.
</P>
<P>
Since the standoff between Iraq and the United States over the
United Nations weapons inspection escalated early the month, the
opposition parties Labor and Meretz voluntarily announced a
political ceasefire by halting tabling non-confidence
motions. They said this ceasefire would help show solidarity
in face of the threat to its national security.
</P>
<P>
Breaking the month-long silence over the government's
performance, Labor lawmakers lashed out Monday at Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and the government for failing to deal with
the crisis properly.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting of Knesset Foreign Affairs and Defense
Committee (FADC) which also include several opposition members,
Netanyahu came under strong criticism for creating unnecessary
panic among the public in the past weeks.
</P>
<P>
Labor lawmaker Eli Goldschmidt blamed the prime minister for
displaying incapability to deal with crises and lacking the
leadership needed to tackle such situation. He was referring to
the government's call on the public to stock gas masks, sealing
materials and food to prepare for a possible Iraqi attack.
</P>
<P>
Another Labor lawmaker Binyamin Ben Eliezer slammed the
government for exposing Israel's softness under bully because of
its poor leadership. He said the government has made "the
strongest people in Middle East was shown scared and in tatters"
during the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Labor's Secretary-General Rannan Cohen declared that
Netanyahu's move has made Iraqi President Saddam Hussein "the King
of Arab world," while weakening the Arab moderates, such as
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Jordan's King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
However, Netanyahu strongly defended the government's behavior
during the crisis, saying that its every step taken was proper
and Israeli defense capability has not been harmed.
</P>
<P>
He said Israel also gained a great deal of valuable experience
from the recent crisis, adding Saddam Hussein in fact respected
Israeli defense capability throughout the crisis. He referred to
the fact that Saddam, unlike what he did during the 1991 Gulf
War, never threatened to attack Israel this time.
</P>
<P>
Uzi Landau, Chairman of the Knesset Foreign Affairs and
Defense Committee, also counter attacked the opposition for its
"cheap exploitation" of the Iraq crisis. But even he himself had
reservations about the government's decision to purchase about
400,000 gas masks and medicines from European countries and the
U.S..
</P>
<P>
Landau, together with Likud veteran lawmaker Benny Begin, said
the money spent on gas masks should be used to purchase
anti-missile defense systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
