<HEADLINE> Bahrain Hails Peaceful Solution to Iraq Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Bahrain Monday welcomed the
agreement signed between Iraq and the U.N. chief Kofi Annan on
arms inspection, the official Bahraini news agency monitored here
reported.
</P>
<P>
In a statement published by the agency, Bahrain's Foreign
Ministry said Manama welcomed "the reaching of the agreement
between Iraq and U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on the Iraq-U.N.
dispute over international arms inspection mission."
</P>
<P>
The peaceful solution "will protect the (Gulf) region's
security and stability" and "will help save the Iraqi people from
further suffering," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It also highly praised Annan's mission in Baghdad, saying the
efforts by the U.N. chief "summed up" all diplomatic efforts and
peaceful drives made for dismantling weapons of mass destruction
in Iraq and averting a military confrontation in the region.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz and Annan signed the
agreement in Baghdad Monday morning with the aim of resolving the
crisis peacefully.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, Baghdad will unconditionally allow
U.N. inspectors charged with dismantling Iraqi weapons of mass
destruction access to all sites suspected of containing biological
or chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the agreement may help defuse a possible military
showdown against Baghdad by the U.S. and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The two Western powers had threatened to launch military attack
on Iraq if Annan's mission to Baghdad starting on Friday failed to
persuade Iraq to back down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
