<HEADLINE> Iran Urges Pakistan to Punish Killers of Iranians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi Monday made a telephone call to his Pakistani
counterpart Gohar Ayub Khan, urging Islamabad to take serious
action to arrest and punish those involved in assassination of
two Iranians in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official news agency IRNA reported that Kharrazi
expressed dismay at the performance of the Pakistani government
in identifying and arresting the terrorist elements involved in
killing Iranian nationals in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He said that regrettably, lack of serious action on the part
of the Islamabad government to deal with the previous cases of
assassinations of Iranian nationals has paved the way for the
continuation of the terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
"We are eagerly anticipating to see the Pakistani government
to take serious action to arrest and punish those involved in
terrorist attacks against the Iranian nationals," he said,
voicing Tehran's readiness to help Islamabad solve security
issues concerning the Iranian nationals in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Ayub Khan expressed condolence to Kharrazi over the killings
of two Iranian engineers and promised that the Pakistani
government would do all it can to put an end to such incidents.
</P>
<P>
The two Iranian engineers, Ali Mohammad Habibzadeh and Mortaza
Adibzadeh, were shot dead in Karachi by unidentified armed men
Saturday afternoon. Pakistani leaders have expressed regret to the
incident.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the state-run television, Kharrazi
stressed that it was not enough to express regret, "for us it is
important to identify, arrest and punish the real terrors."
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran would soon send a delegation to Pakistan to
investigate the issue, adding that the Pakistani government
should take more serious measures to fight against terrorist
activities in order that relations between the two neighbors
would not be damaged by such crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
