<HEADLINE> Annan: Use of Military Force Unnecessary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, February 23 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said here Monday that the signing of the
Iraq-U.N. agreement on weapons inspection made it unnecessary for
the United States to resort to force against Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
"I think everyone is relieved that we were able to defuse the
crisis and the use of military force will not be necessary,"
Annan told reporters after meeting Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan
during his stopover in Amman en route to Paris.
</P>
<P>
"We had very useful, frank, honest and constructive
discussions in Baghdad. We had successful talks," said the U.N.
secretary general. he refused to elaborate on details of the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that he hoped all the Security Council members would
accept the agreement when he submitted it to them in New York
later so that Iraq as well as the region could be spared
disasters.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief expressed appreciation for Jordan's efforts in
helping defuse the tension.
</P>
<P>
"The king (Hussein) is one of the leaders in the region and is
someone who understands also the situation in Iraq and is someone
I have been working with, seeking his support and help to defuse
the situation," he added.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that he made a telephone call to the king after
concluding the agreement with the Iraqi government.
</P>
<P>
"When we succeeded, I called him to tell him what we have
done and thanked him for his cooperation and support."
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Hassan told reporters that he hoped the
agreement would lead to a solution to the crisis over arms
inspections and put an end to the plight of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Hassan said that Annan did not brief him on the details of the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Annan and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz signed the
agreement Monday morning in Baghdad. The U.N. chief is expected to
submit it to the Security Council soon for discussion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
