<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-23 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Will of Peace Overpowers Threat of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Neither Iraqi nor U.S. leaders
are entitled to claim the winner in the Iraq crisis that was
eased, if not totally defused, with the signing of a U.N.-brokered
agreement Monday -- the prevailing will of peace is.
</P>
<P>
Many analysts said Iraq was playing games or tricks with the
U.S. in the crisis so as to attract world's attention to its
sufferings of the seven-year-old U.N. sanctions, believing it has
won the game without losing anything.
</P>
<P>
Others said the United States has succeeded in forcing Iraq
down to kneels by a huge military buildup in the region.
</P>
<P>
But the key factor is that the agreement would have been
impossible if without the will of peace across the
world. Addressing a press conference, U.N. chief Kofi Annan
especially expressed his thanks to the world leaders and peoples
who contributed to the success of his peace mission in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Annan and Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz. No details were disclosed but Annan said that
if the accord is carried out honestly, there would not be more
problems.
</P>
<P>
The crisis was triggered as Iraq denied access of sensitive
places like presidential sites to U.N. weapons inspectors. It also
said the U.S. and Britain, whose personnel take important
positions in the inspection teams, were willingly delaying the
lifting of U.N. sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain were quick enough to unleash their threat
of military attack on Iraq if it does not change stand.
</P>
<P>
Obviously determined are the U.S. and Britain to launch
"substantial" attack on Iraq, but facts undoubtedly suggest that
the two world powers feel weak in boasting the moral support
garnered from their own citizens and allies.
</P>
<P>
Many Americans posed the question: if Iraqi Leader Saddam
Hussein is to blame for all the wrongdoings as said, why should
the Iraqi people bear the sufferings of a war. No answer was
strong enough to calm down an increasingly high uproar for a
peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and British leaders have been warned of the backfire
of the possible war: accusation of killing innocent Iraqis,
losing Arab friends, expected casualties of armed troops, war cost
and its impact on economy, a destabilized regional situation and so
on.
</P>
<P>
What is more eye-catching is that three other permanent members
of the United Nations Security council, namely China, Russia and
France, firmly oppose the use of force. Their positions surely
have backed the success of Annan's peace mission.
</P>
<P>
In fact, most of the other countries, especially Arabs, have
expressed their opposition to war and some, like Egypt and Jordan,
were active in mediation. Few Arab allies announced support to a
military attack.
</P>
<P>
Call for peace is now too loud to be ignored by Washington and
London who have to condition the wage of raid on failure of
diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
On the part of Iraq, the showing of flexibility in negotiations
with Annan, as a move in a game or whatever strategy, can be
regarded as an effort that paves way for a peaceful solution --
the will of peace prevailed over anything and worked.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, an overwhelming hail of the Baghdad accord heard
across the world is a demonstration of the power of peace as
against war threat.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have not canceled their war plan and the
crisis is far from over, but as Annan said "You can never
underestimate the power of prayer (for peace)." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Willing to Back ECOMOG Efforts in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States is willing to
support the efforts of the Nigerian-led west African peacekeeping
force (ECOMOG) in Sierra Leone, the News Agency of Nigeria
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. would be ready to assist in the airlifting of troops
from west African countries that have indicated to contribute
additional troops to ECOMOG in maintaining peace in that country
following the ejection of the military junta, the official agency
said, quoting U.S. ambassador to Nigeria William Twaddell.
</P>
<P>
However, a request had to be made to the U.S. and approved by
the U.S. congress, the envoy said in the Nigerian capital Abuja
at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
According to Twaddell, the U.S. had set a precedent in Liberia
where it contributed 90 million U.S. Dollars and assisted in the
airlifting of troops from some west African countries for the
peacekeeping operation.
</P>
<P>
Twaddell's remarks came in the wake of a U.S. State Department
statement last Thursday that promised succor to the civilian
population in Sierra Leone, who are said to be suffering from a
lack of food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
The envoy also explained his country's initiative on the
formation of a standing African peacekeeping force, saying that
it is intended to enable the continent to respond quickly to
emergencies.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to the notion that the initiative was intended to
encourage foreign domination, it would encourage collaboration
with other countries in tackling emergencies in Africa, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has been contributing three million Dollars annually
to conflict resolution in Africa, Twaddell said, adding that the
initiative should be seen as part of a contingency plan to equip
African countries with a quick response capability.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has consistently rejected an external initiative for
conflict resolution on the continent, arguing that Africans are
in the best position to determine appropriate approach.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian head of state General Sani Abacha has indicated it is
a good way to form an African peacekeeping force with ECOMOG as
nuclear. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
