<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Lawmakers Wary of Annan's Deal on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. lawmakers Monday
reacted warily to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's deal with
Baghdad over the weapons inspection crisis in Iraq, calling for
immediate military action if Iraq does not live up to terms
necessary for carrying out U.N. weapons resolutions.
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Newt Gingrich said he hoped the agreement reached
by Annan and Iraq officials would avoid a conflict between
Washington and Baghdad by making Iraq a chemical and biological
weapons-free country.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that Annan has gotten a good agreement and I hope it is
one that guarantees a chemical and biological weapons-free Iraq,"
Gingrich said at a gathering of business leaders in Smyrna,
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Clinton administration to be ready for immediate
action against Baghdad if Iraqi President Saddam Hussein fails to
live up to the terms set by the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Republican Senator John McCain told the business leaders before
Gingrich's remarks that he was concerned that even if the issue
was resolved for now, it was far from over.
</P>
<P>
"I think in the short term, we have averted a situation where
American lives would have been lost," he said. "But in the long
term, I am still deeply concerned because I have received no
indication Saddam Hussein has changed his commitment to acquiring
and using weapons of mass destruction."
</P>
<P>
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said President Clinton may be
"in a box" -- stuck with a poor agreement he has to accept.
</P>
<P>
"I was worried that this initiative by Annan was going to put
the president in a box and that's exactly what's happened," Lott
told reporters at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
"This is another example of how the administration's foreign
policy is subcontracted to other.... Everybody says this is good
enough, and yet it may not be good enough," He said. "But the
president would be in such a box because of the way it was handled
he had no alternative."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with CNN, Republican Senator Arlen Specter said
that even if Annan's deal is solid, the U.S. government should
step up efforts to oust Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
"One way or another we're going to have to topple Saddam
Hussein" to ensure that he does not build weapons of mass
destruction, he told CNN.
</P>
<P>
He said he planned to propose that Saddam be brought before an
international war crimes tribunal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
