<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-23 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt: More Steps Needed to Implement UN-Iraq Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Egypt said Monday "some other
steps" are needed to be taken to put into practice the U.N.-Iraqi
deal on resolving the arms inspection crisis peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Giving credit to the agreement signed by U.N. chief Kofi Annan
and the Iraqi government Monday, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa lauded it as "a key stride" in the international drive to
defuse the crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, Moussa told reporters that the deal has not been
submitted to the U.N. Security Council for approval.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt is awaiting this and following up the situation," he
stressed. However, he said he could not elaborate on future steps,
given that details of the agreement has not yet been unveiled.
</P>
<P>
But he said the agreement, signed by Annan and Iraqi Deputy
Prime Minister Tariq Aziz in Baghdad, has the "official nature"
and meets all requirements of the parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that the agreement will defuse regional tension," he
added.
</P>
<P>
In his first reaction to the conclusion of the Iraqi-U.N. deal
Monday morning, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak expressed hope
that the U.S. would back the agreement in the Security Council and
voiced fear that any violation of the deal will drag the region
into a "terrible situation."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has insisted that any agreement must allow
U.N. weapons inspectors free and full access to all sites and
maintain the integrity of the U.N. Special Commission charged with
scrapping Iraqi weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough in settling the crisis came after rounds of
intensive talks Annan held with Iraqi leaders since his
arrival in Baghdad Friday in a last-ditch effort to bring about a
political solution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
