<HEADLINE> UNITA Still Blocks Peace Process in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, February 23 (Xinhua) -- The opposition National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) is still trying to
block the peace process by creating troubles in some places of
Angola, local media reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that in the latest developments, nearly 20
UNITA soldiers launched an attack against Catata town in central
Huambo Province, committing atrocities to local civilians.
</P>
<P>
The looting, kidnaping and beating by the UNITA soldiers has
thrown local people into panic and threatened stability in the
region, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA has also set barriers before the re-establishment of
local governments in the areas under its control. It tried its
best to check the efforts to re-set up local governments in Jamba
and Licua in southeast Kuando-Kubango Province.
</P>
<P>
So far, no progress has been achieved in the talks between the
Angolan government and the UNITA on the issue.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the purpose of the UNITA on the issue, military
sources disclosed that the UNITA is mapping a new military plan
which considers Jamba and Licua as strategic points. The two
places are also hiding a great number of UNITA soldiers, they
added. 
</P>
