<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-23 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OIC Welcomes Deal Signed by UN Chief, Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 23 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of
Islamic Conference (OIC) Monday welcomed the deal signed in
Baghdad between U.N. Chief Kofi Annan and Iraq on resolving the
Iraq-U.N. standoff over weapons inspection.
</P>
<P>
Ezzidine Laraki, secretary general of the Jeddah (Saudi
Arabia)-based organization, said in a statement that he hoped "the
deal would put an end to the crisis and (U.S.) threats to launch
military strikes against Iraq," Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
After several rounds of talks, Annan signed the agreement with
Iraq Monday morning to try to end the Iraq crisis peacefully.
</P>
<P>
The deal was said to have settled all the major issues in
Iraq's dispute with the U.N. over weapons inspections. But details
of the agreement will be disclosed only after Annan returns to
New York Tuesday and submits it to the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The OIC has expressed its support for a diplomatic solution to
the crisis and urged Iraq to fully comply with the
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Saudi Arabia, Oman and Qatar also joined a number of
Arab states and the Arab League Monday in welcoming the deal.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi Cabinet, during a weekly meeting chaired by King
Fahd Ibn Abdul Aziz, expressed its satisfaction of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Information Minister Fuad Farisi was quoted by Saudi
Press Agency as reiterating Saudi Arabia's stand that Iraq should
comply with all the U.N. resolutions so as to guarantee the
security and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
In Doha, Qatari Foreign Minister Sheikh Hamad Bin Jassim Bin
Jabir Al-Thani said the agreement constitutes a positive step
toward Iraq's compliance with all U.N. resolutions, adding that
the agreement would spare the people of Iraq the hardship of war.
</P>
<P>
In Muscat, Oman's capital, a Foreign Ministry spokesman also
expressed his country's welcome of the agreement and thanked
Annan for his efforts to clinch the deal.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait also cautiously welcomed the agreement although it
wondered whether the agreement involved full Iraqi implementation
of all U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait Crown Prince and Prime Minister Sheikh Saad Al-Abdulla
Al-Salem Al-Sabah was quoted by Kuwait News Agency as saying that
"the agreement with Iraq needs more studying, we must read what
is between the lines."
</P>
<P>
But Kuwait Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sheikh
Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah Al-Sabah said that Kuwait is "happy for
any agreement signed to spare the region the dangers and at the
same time make Iraq comply with Security Council resolutions. But
we must first see the details of this agreement."
</P>
<P>
Egypt, Jordan, Syria, the Palestinian National Authority,
Tunisia, Algeria and the Arab League also welcomed the deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
