<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Former President Pledged Not Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 23 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's former
state president Pieter Botha Monday pledged not guilty to charges
of ignoring summons to appear before the Truth and Reconciliation
Commission.
</P>
<P>
Botha, who is 82 years old, appeared in court Monday morning
after refusing to give evidence before the commission, a
government-appointed special court hearing crimes committed under
apartheid.
</P>
<P>
Botha's lawyer, Lappe Laubscher, argues the commission has
broken a promise not to require the former head of state to
attend a commission hearing in person.
</P>
<P>
The lawyer accuses the commission of acting maliciously toward
Botha and of bias for claiming most of its members are supporters
of the ruling African National Congress.
</P>
<P>
The commission had called Botha to testify before the hearing
in December for his leadership of the now-defunct State Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
The council's task was to enforce the racial segregation
policies of the white-minority regime.
</P>
<P>
Last week, South African President Nelson Mandela held talks
with Botha's family over his continued refusal to appear before
the commission, chaired by retired Anglican archbishop Desmond
Tutu. 
</P>
