<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court Rejects Ruby Ridge Civil Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 23 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Court of the
United States Monday rejected a review of an appeals court ruling
that allows a civil suit against federal officials arising out of
the Ruby Ridge standoff in Idaho in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Kevin Harris, a friend of white separatist Randy Weaver, filed
the suit, contending that the U.S. marshals, FBI agents and
officials in both agencies conspired to deprive him of his rights.
</P>
<P>
Six U.S. marshals were sent to Ruby Ridge to serve a warrant on
a weapons charge against Weaver. As they staked out the remote
hillside, they were discovered and engaged in a shootout with
Weaver, Harris and Weaver's 14-year-old son Samuel. Samuel Weaver
and a federal marshal were killed in the firefight.
</P>
<P>
Later, a member of the FBI's Hostage Rescue Team fired shots at
Harris and Weaver, believing the men were firing at a government
helicopter from the Weaver compound. He fired at Harris as he dove
back into the Weaver house. The round passed through Harris and
killed Weaver's wife.
</P>
<P>
In his suit, Harris claimed that marshals lied about the
initial firefight, and that the FBI's aggressive rules of
engagement led the sharpshooter to wound him.
</P>
<P>
When a federal judge threw out some of Harris's claims but left
others intact and an appeals court agreed, a group of the federal
law enforcement officers asked the Supreme Court for review, which
was denied Monday without comment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
