<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-23 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Urges Follow-up Steps to End Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi chief delegate to the Arab
League Nabil Nejm said here Monday that Baghdad needs follow-up
steps to put an end to the sanctions against the Iraqi people
after it signed a deal with the U.N. Chief Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
"Today's agreement between Baghdad and the U.N. is a step on
the right path that must be followed by others towards the lifting
of sanctions on the Iraqi people," Nejm told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Annan and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz Monday signed
the agreement on reaching a political solution to the crisis over
arms inspection. But the deal still needs the ratification of the
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Sanctions on Iraq imposed after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait can
not be removed until the council verifies Iraq has destroyed all
its long-range missiles and weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Nejm refused to call the agreement as a concession by this or
that party, saying that it is "rather a balanced political
solution taking into account the interests of all parties
concerned, foremost Iraq's right to sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
He said his country's ultimate aim is to arrive at a political
solution that preserves its legitimate rights.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-Iraq standoff has been escalating since last November
when Iraq refused to give U.N. arms inspectors unfettered access
to its presidential compounds on grounds of sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Nejm also slammed the U.S. claim that under U.N. Security
Council resolution 687 which allegedly invests the U.S. with the
right to use force, Washington does not need a U.N. approval to
attack Iraq if diplomatic efforts fail.
</P>
<P>
"There is nothing in the Security Council resolutions that
authorizes the use of force against Iraq," said the Iraqi
official, adding that "its insistence on using force is evidence
that it has no respect for the international will."
</P>
<P>
The U.S., a permanent member of the Security Council, has
insisted that any agreement must allow unrestricted access to all
sites and the integrity of the U.N. Special Commission on
scrapping Iraqi weapons of mass destruction. Otherwise, it will
attack Iraq to force its compliance with U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough came as a result of tough talks Annan held
with Iraqi leaders since Friday in a last-ditch attempt to seek
Iraqi implementation of U.N. resolutions and avert imminent
U.S. military attack on Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
