<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dolly's Creators Go on to Clone Calf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 23 (Xinhua) -- PPL Therapeutics, the British
company that helped to create Dolly, world's first adult clone,
announced on Monday that it has also cloned a calf.
</P>
<P>
The healthy 44.5 kg animal, called Mr Jefferson, produced by
PPL's subsidiary in American, was born in Virginia on February 16,
the company said.
</P>
<P>
The technique used to create the calf was similar to that used
to produce Dolly, but Mr Jefferson was produced by nuclear
transfer from a foetal cell, not from an adult one.
</P>
<P>
Though the calf is not transgenic, carrying no human genes, the
company said the animal's birth opened the way to producing
transgenic cows, whose milk could eventually be used to treat
disease in humans.
</P>
<P>
PPL, one of the world's leading companies in the transgenic
production of human proteins in the milk of livestock, announced
together with Scotland's Roslin Institute the successful
production of Dolly the cloned sheep exactly a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Some scientists recently claimed that Dolly might not be a
genuine clone, saying that it may not come from an adult cell at
all.
</P>
<P>
In response to these speculations. the PPL defended Monday that
the company "is confident that Dolly was produced from an adult
mammary cell."
</P>
<P>
The creation of Mr Jefferson, the company said, shows "we have
the capability to extend the technique to cattle." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
