<HEADLINE> Jordan's King Hails Iraq-UN Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, February 23 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan welcomed
the agreement signed by Iraq and the U.N. Chief Kofi Annan in
Baghdad Monday, expressing the hope that the accord would
contribute to achieving a peaceful solution to the
Iraq-U.N. crisis over arms inspection.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that this agreement has put an end to the charged
atmosphere in which we have been living" and put an end to the
Iraqi people's sufferings, said Hussein in an interview with
Jordan Television Station.
</P>
<P>
The concerned sides should then focus on the issue of the
U.N. sanctions on Iraq imposed after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait,
he added.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the Iraqi people will be able to get out of the dark
tunnel to a new dawn and live a free and dignified life on their
soil," he said.
</P>
<P>
After rounds of talks, Annan and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz signed the agreement Monday morning. Annan has left for
New York and is expected to submit the agreement to the Security
Council members Tuesday for approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
