<HEADLINE> Clinton Cautiously Supports Annan's Deal on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Monday cautiously supported a tentative agreement signed by
Secretary General of the United Nations Kofi Annan and Iraqi
Deputy Prime Minister Teqec Aziz that was aimed to avert military
action against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"I hope today's agreement will prove to be the step forward
that we had been looking for," Clinton told an Oval Office news
conference.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraqi President Saddam Hussein had for the first time
since the 1991 Gulf War promised unfettered access to his
presidential areas.
</P>
<P>
But Clinton said whether Saddam allows weapons inspectors
unlimited access to his presidential palaces remains "a big if."
</P>
<P>
"The proof is in the testing," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said there will be serious consequences if Iraq once
again fails to allow complete inspections of suspected weapons
sites.
</P>
<P>
He said if Iraq doesn't keep its word this time, everyone in
the United States and its allies would recognize that the United
States has the right to respond. And the United States will keep
its forces in the Gulf for military action once Saddam breaks
his words by his deeds.
</P>
<P>
"I intend to keep our forces at high levels of preparation,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
