<HEADLINE> U.S. Gov't Drops Charges Against 2 Men in Anthrax Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government Monday
dismissed charges against two men of conspiring to possess deadly
anthrax that could be used as a weapon.
</P>
<P>
Harris and William Leavitt Jr. were arrested last Wednesday in
suburban Henderson, south of Las Vegas. Weekend tests showed the
material was actually a harmless anthrax vaccine for animals and
additional tests showed that material seized from Harris' Ohio
home also was a safe vaccine.
</P>
<P>
Lawyers for Leavitt and Harris said their clients were not
terrorists, but scientists who planned to use the anthrax vaccine
to test an unorthodox disease-killing machine from a man who
tipped of the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI).
</P>
<P>
Federal prosecutors said in a statement that they had to act
swiftly because of evidence suggesting the men intended to test
vials of the deadly anthrax bacteria.
</P>
<P>
Leavitt was freed, but Harris remained jailed on a new charge
filed in Columbus, Ohio, that he violated terms of his probation
for a 1995 conviction on illegally ordering freeze-dried bubonic
plague bacteria by mail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
