<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Records No Consumer Inflation in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The United States recorded
no monthly consumer inflation in January for the first time in
nearly four years thanks to the biggest drop in energy prices, the
Labor Department reported here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Consumer prices overall were unchanged, marking the first month
without an increase since January 1994, the department noted.
</P>
<P>
But Energy costs dropped by 2.4 percent, the largest decrease
since March 1991. They are 25 percent lower than a year ago and,
with crude oil prices still falling, they'll likely continue the
trend.
</P>
<P>
Food prices rose a moderate 0.3 percent in January, pushed up
by a 7.9 percent increase in fresh vegetables, including a 33
percent increase in lettuce.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile food and energy categories, prices
climbed a modest 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. inflation last year was just 1.7 percent, the mildest
rate since the crash of oil prices in 1986, and economists see
little reason for the rate to move above 2 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The major threat of inflation may come through services. Their
prices may be pushed up by rising wages stemming from shortages of
labor. However, in January, service prices rose just 0.1 percent,
while good prices declined 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Last month's energy decline was led by a 3.6 percent drop in
gasoline. Fuel oil and natural gas both were down 2.7 percent and
electricity, 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Declining beef, pork, poultry, fruit and coffee prices helped
moderate the big vegetable prices increase and a moderate rise in
dairy products.
</P>
<P>
Outside food and energy, clothing costs fell 0.5 percent.
Medical care and new cars and trucks rose only 0.1 percent.
However, tobacco products jumped 0.7 percent and airline fares,
2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Communication costs, a new category, fell 0.4 percent, pulled
down by a drop in cellular phone costs. But recreation rose 0.3
percent, reflecting a 1.7 percent rise for cable television.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
