<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Reiterates Bilateral Agreement on Caspian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 24 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iranian official said
here Tuesday that any bilateral agreement on the destiny of the
Caspian Sea is an "invalid act and against international norms and
regulations."
</P>
<P>
Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister for legal and international
affairs Mohammad Javad Zarif made the remarks on the eve of a
visit by Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Zarif was quoted by the Iranian official news agency as saying
that under an agreement reached earlier by the foreign ministers
of the five littoral states, the Caspian Sea legal regime can be
defined and completed through consensus of all five states
bordering the sea.
</P>
<P>
Any measure adopted by each of the Caspian Sea littoral states
should not be detrimental to other littoral states, or else it
would lack political and legal basis, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zarif said that contribution of all the littoral states to a
political dialogue coupled with good will would be the
prerequisite for a lasting agreement which guarantees balanced
and logical interests of all the states concerned.
</P>
<P>
Such an agreement is attainable and possible only by honoring
the rights and interests of all the states bordering the Caspian
Sea, he said. He called on the five littoral countries to speed up
the process to determine the legal regime for the world largest
inner-land lake.
</P>
<P>
Zarif rejected any rivalry and interference in the region by
countries which do not border the sea, saying that "the task of
forging the legal regime for the Caspian Sea rests with the
littoral states and others should not interfere in it."
</P>
<P>
He said that exploitation of the sea's natural resources could
be possible within the framework of a regime agreed upon
unanimously by all the littoral states, adding that convergence
is the only way to development and progress for the Caspian Sea
and its littoral states.
</P>
<P>
He underlined the importance to announce the Caspian sea
as a non-military zone, saying that permanent security of the sea
was tied to keeping the region a non-military zone.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi was scheduled to leave here for Moscow Tuesday
afternoon to discuss with Russian officials the latest regional
developments, especially the Iraq crisis and the Caspian Sea
legal regime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Dismisses US Dual Containment on Moscow, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi Tuesday dismissed the idea that Washington was after a
dual containment policy against Moscow and Tehran in its recent
military buildup in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question at the opening session of the Persian Gulf
seminar, Kharrazi said that the U.S. strengthened its military
deployment in the Gulf region with the aim to resolve
Baghdad-Washington disputes over arms inspection.
</P>
<P>
The question was raised on the eve of an official visit by the
Iranian foreign minister to Moscow, which will start Tuesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
As a permanent member of the U.N. Security Council, Russia is
an important country in the region and the world, Kharrazi said,
adding that Moscow shared the same views with Tehran towards the
Iraq-U.N. crisis that it should be resolved through diplomatic
efforts instead of military measures.
</P>
<P>
Iranian press recently quoted Iranian political analysts as
saying that one of the objectives behind the U.S. military
buildup in the region is to weaken the Baghdad government in
order to change its dual containment on Iraq and Iran into a new
form on Iran and Russia.
</P>
<P>
As a long-term strategy, foreign diplomats here also said,
Washington's military buildup in the region could be interpreted
as an extension of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization eastward
expansion aiming at containing both Moscow and Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Russia and Iran showed their strong opposition to a possible
U.S. military strike on Iraq if diplomatic efforts failed to
persuade Iraq to give full access to U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
After rounds of talks, U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan and
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz signed an agreement Monday
in Baghdad on peacefully ending the Iraq-U.N. crisis.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said that the peaceful solution of the U.N.-Iraq
standoff indicated that the U.S. is no longer in a position to
dictate its views to others.
</P>
<P>
Referring to his visit to Moscow, Kharrazi said that issues
and problems of the Caspian Sea, the peace process in Tajikistan
and Tehran-Moscow economic cooperation are at the top of his
agenda of talks with Russian officials.
</P>
<P>
He said that one of the objectives of the Iranian foreign
policies was to establish friendly and sincere ties and
cooperation with Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
