<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 14:30 GMT February 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN -- Germany saw new car registrations dropped to 261,646 in
January, 1.7 percent less than a year before, the Federal Vehicles
Office Tuesday reported in Flensburg.
</P>
<P>
The office noted that total vehicle registrations came to 292,799,
a drop of only 0.5 percent from January 1997, thanks to a rise in
registrations of trucks, motocycles, tractor-trailers and buses.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Volkswagen took the lead in private new car
registrations with 55,349, followed by Ford with 31,733. Opel came
after with 31,673, and Mercedes-Benz with 25,896. (German-Car)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Tokyo stocks tumbled Tuesday on despair over Japan's
poor economic outlook, spurred by pessimistic earnings projections
for the current business year.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First section
at the Tokyo Stock Exchange plunged 411.49 points, or 2.48
percent, from Monday to close at 16,198.00.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
issues on the First Section, declined 19.81 points, or 1.58
percent, to 1,234.77. (Japan-Stock-Exchange)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HANOI -- The Communist Manifesto with its spirit and vitality
continues to light the revolutionary road and renewal process in
Vietnam, the Nhan Dan daily said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In an editorial to mark the 150th anniversary of the Communist
Manifesto, the national daily of the Communist Party described the
document, written by Karl Marx in February 1848, as the banner for
emancipation.
</P>
<P>
The editorial said that Marxism with the Communist Manifesto as
its ideological foundation achieved a new importance under Lenin
during the period of imperialism on "the eve of proletarian
revolution."  (Vietnam-Editorial-Manifesto)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea enjoyed a trade surplus of 1.51 billion
U.S. dollars last month, despite its serious financial crisis,
said the Customs administration department on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In January, exports edged up 0.3 percent from 9.034 billion
U.S. dollars thanks largely to export of gold worth 683 million
dollars. Imports stood at 7.554 billion dollars, a drop of 39.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
However, without gold exports, January would have seen a 7.2
percent or 650-million-dollar export decline from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
South Korea suffered a trade deficit of 3.476 billion dollars
in January 1997. (Skorea-Trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The European Union (EU) has approved a humanitarian
aid package to Iraq after its agreement of a weapons inspection
deal with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The aid package, worth 10 million ECU (10.8 million U.S.
dollars), brings the total EU humanitarian aid to Iraq since 1991
to 217.67 million ECU.
</P>
<P>
The aid, managed by EU's European Community Humanitarian
Office, will enable humanitarian organizations from six European
countries to carry out a coordinated program over the next 10
months.
</P>
<P>
The aid program will focus on support for malnourished
children, assistance to victims of landmines, renovation of water
supplies, and the repair of hospitals, water and sanitation
services. (EU-Emergency-Iraq)  
</P>
