<HEADLINE> US Religious Delegation Holds Talks with Tibetan Clergy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The visiting US religious
leaders had a conversation here this afternoon with local
religious figures on issues of common interest.
</P>
<P>
The US delegation includes Rabbi Arthur Schneier, president of
the Appeal of Conscience Foundation of the United States,
Archbishop Theodore McCarrick of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of
Newark, and the Rev. Don Argue, president of the National
Association of Evangelicals.
</P>
<P>
Living Buddha Jiare Lobsang Danzim, deputy director of the
Ethnic and Religious Affairs Committee of the Tibet Autonomous
Region, briefed the visitors on the situation of religion in
Tibet.
</P>
<P>
He told the visitors that there are more than 1,600 temples
and other religious sites, and over 46,000 monks and nuns in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
McCarrick said the Tibetan visit had special significance for
him, as it is the first time an archbishop of the Roman Catholic
Church has visited the region.
</P>
<P>
Schneier and his companions showed concern about the severe
snowstorm in northern Tibet, and said that he hoped they could
provide some aid to the area.
</P>
<P>
Requested by the visitors to make a comment on the Dalai Lama,
Living Buddha Cemolin Danzengchilie said, "I have faith in the
Dalai Lama as a religious figure, but I object to his
activities overseas aimed at splitting the motherland."
</P>
<P>
Lobsang Gyaincain, mayor of this capital of the region, also
met with the US religious leaders here tonight.  
</P>
</TEXT>
