<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Religious Delegation Visits Potala Palace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- A delegation of US religious
figures today visited the Potala Palace and the Jokhang Temple in
this capital of the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Included in the delegation are Rabbi Arthur Schneier, president
of the Appeal of Conscience Foundation of the United States,
Archbishop Theodore McCarrick of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of
Newark and the Rev. Don Argue, president of the National
Association of Evangelicals.
</P>
<P>
A guide told the visitors at the fifth Dalai Lama's Soul Pagoda
in the the 117-m-high Potala Palace that the fifth Dalai Lama,
famous in Tibetan history, traveled to Beijing in 1652 for a
meeting with Emperor Shunzhi of the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911).
</P>
<P>
The Soul Pagoda, where the remains of the fifth Dalai Lama are
preserved, is coated in 3,720 kg of gold.
</P>
<P>
Coins from various countries placed at the foot of the pagoda
are donations from tourists and religious believers and intended
to maintain the palace.
</P>
<P>
Schneier donated a new designed 100-US-dollar note to the
palace, and said that donation and sharing are good things in
Judaism and Christianity.
</P>
<P>
It is the same in Buddhism, the guide told him.
</P>
<P>
The palace is divided into two parts: the Red Palace, where the
Soul Pagodas of the various Dalai Lamas and halls for worshiping
Buddha are located; and the White Palace, where the Dalai Lamas
lived and conducted political affairs.
</P>
<P>
After walking around the Potala Palace for more than one hour,
the US visitors came to a lounge where an inscription written by
President Jiang Zemin during his visit in 1990 is suspended from
the ceiling. The inscription encourages all people to maintain
ethnic unity and carry forward ethnic culture.
</P>
<P>
A manager of the palace told the visitors that the central
government of China pays great attention to protecting cultural
relics in Tibet, and has earmarked 53 million yuan (about 6.4
million US dollars) to maintain the palace.
</P>
<P>
Schneier wondered whether any Tibetans were involved in the
maintenance of the palace. The man answered that such work is
mostly done by local Tibetans, as well as experts and technicians
from China's State Bureau of Cultural Relics.
</P>
<P>
About 20,000 foreign tourists visit the Potala Palace each
year, in addition to a large number of worshippers, he added.
</P>
<P>
The US visitors then went to the Jokhang Temple.
</P>
<P>
As the Tibetan new year is approaching, the square in front of
the temple was crowded with a large number of worshippers. The US
visitors recorded the scene with ordinary cameras and video
cameras.
</P>
<P>
The temple, one of earliest buildings constructed in Tibet,
preserves a host of valuable cultural relics, including a statue
of Sakyamuni taken there by Princess Wencheng of the Tang Dynasty
(618-907).
</P>
<P>
The US visitors took pictures of the statue with the permission
of the temple management.
</P>
<P>
Nema Tsering, deputy director of management committee of the
temple, told the visitors in English that 115 lamas chant
scriptures at night because they are busy running the temple duing
the daytime.
</P>
<P>
The US delegation visited Beijing, Nanjing and Shanghai before
they went to Lhasa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
