<HEADLINE> UNHCR Head Urges to Solve Refugee Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The visiting United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), Sadako Ogata
Tuesday called on all countries to work together to solve the
refugee problem in the world.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing here, Ogata said refugee problem
cannot be solved unilaterally and it needs all countries to work
together for it.
</P>
<P>
She said, "unless asylum countries take responsibilities for
the refugee problem, it will be very difficult to the UNHCR alone
to solve it."
</P>
<P>
She said that two major problems in this regard are refugees
being expelled by asylum countries and refugees carrying out
insurgency activities in asylum countries.
</P>
<P>
"These twin problems have to be addressed more seriously and
compatible arrangements should be sought to tackle them," she
noted.
</P>
<P>
Ogata is currently on a nine-nation African tour.
</P>
<P>
Talking on her current visit to Africa, she said the purpose
of her mission is to listen to the concerns of leaders,
particularly those in the Great Lakes region, where UNHCR
continues to be involved in major operations for Rwandan and
Burundian refugees and returnee.
</P>
<P>
She said that she had explored ways of promoting greater
adherence to humanitarian principles and refugee conventions.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR commissioner arrived here Sunday for a four-day
visit to Ethiopia which is the last leg of her nine-nation
African tour.
</P>
<P>
The other eight countries are Zimbabwe, Tanzania, Burundi,
Rwanda, Kenya, Uganda, the Democratic Republic of Congo and the
Republic of Congo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
