<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Tighten Control Over Outdoor Noise Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Gardeners may soon have to be
careful in choosing when to mow their lawns and buying their
machines as the European Union decided Tuesday to tighten controls
on outdoor noise levels.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive agency of the 15-nation
union, proposed to the European Parliament and the EU Council of
Ministers to regulate the noise emission of equipment used
outdoors.
</P>
<P>
The equipment in question includes construction machinery such
as cranes, excavators, hammers, loaders and compressors as well as
gardening machines such as lawnmowers, chainsaws, leaf blowers and
shredders.
</P>
<P>
If the parliament and council pass the proposal, the new
legislation will update and replace the nine current stipulations
covering separate groups of machines.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the proposal is to protect the health and well-being
of citizens by reducing exposure to noise and the nuisance caused
by outdoor machinery.
</P>
<P>
An essential element of the proposal is to recommend that
machines are marked with their maximum noise emission level,
thereby enabling buyers to make an informed choice.
</P>
<P>
The commission's proposal for legislation on outdoor noise
emission covers 55 types of equipment.
</P>
<P>
The proposal also defines noise test codes, as the noise limit
values are essentially based on the way noise emissions are
measured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
