<HEADLINE> Chinese Journalists Encouraged to Uncover Environmental Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Qu Geping, chairman of the
Environmental and Resources Protection Committee (ERPC) of China's
National People's Congress, has asked journalists to faithfully
report the country's environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
Qu said at an environmental protection meeting here today that
supervision must be enhanced to guarantee the effective
implementation of the laws, and media supervision is an important
complement to the judicial supervision of the National People's
Congress.
</P>
<P>
He said that the press should voice the public's concerns and
demands. "Pollution infringes upon the people's interests and
impairs their health," Qu stressed.
</P>
<P>
China's environmental situation is serious, and the
deterioration of the environment has not yet been curbed. The area
affected by acid rain accounts for about 28 percent of the
country's total.
</P>
<P>
In addition, nearly half of the country's seven major rivers
are polluted. Groundwater in urban areas is also contaminated
seriously.
</P>
<P>
China has promulgated 15 laws concerning environmental and
resources protection over the past decade. However, Qu said, some
of them have not been effectively implemented.
</P>
<P>
The ERPC has organized more than 6,000 reporters to cover the
country's major environmental problems over the past five years,
and they have dispatched more than 40,000 environmental news
reports, which have contributed to the settlement of some of the
problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
