<HEADLINE> EU Clears Emergency Aid to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
approved a humanitarian aid package to Iraq after its agreement of
a weapons inspection deal with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The aid package, worth 10 million ECU (10.8 million U.S.
dollars), brings the total EU humanitarian aid to Iraq since 1991
to 217.67 million ECU.
</P>
<P>
The aid, managed by EU's European Community Humanitarian
Office, will enable humanitarian organizations from six European
countries to carry out a coordinated program over the next 10
months.
</P>
<P>
The aid program will focus on support for malnourished
children, assistance to victims of landmines, renovation of water
supplies, and the repair of hospitals, water and sanitation
services.
</P>
<P>
There will also be support for children in special institutions
for the handicapped and orphans.
</P>
<P>
The EU humanitarian office said that it would continue
monitoring humanitarian needs in Iraq and intended to re-evaluate
the situation in the country later this year.
</P>
<P>
EU foreign ministers, who met on Monday, agreed to support the
weapons inspection deal reached between United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan and the Iraqi authorities.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation union supported efforts to find a diplomatic
solution to the crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
