<HEADLINE> 200 Zanzibar Residents Plan Pilgrimage to Mecca </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Some 200 Moslems in the
Zanzibar isles plan to go on a pilgrimage to the holy city of
Mecca in Saudi Arabia, media reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A government official dealing with Islamic affairs in the
isles, Abdallah Talib, told reporters Monday that the number has
shot up from 150 last year.
</P>
<P>
Each pilgrim has to pay 1.1 million shillings (about 1,680
U.S. Dollars) for the trip, compared with 990,448 shillings last
year, Talib said, noting that the price will cover air tickets,
visa charges, and other services to be rendered in Mecca.
</P>
<P>
The official attributed the price rise to the increased
accommodation costs in Mecca.
</P>
<P>
The government will soon appoint an official to lead the
pilgrims, he said. The pilgrims will board an Ethiopian Airlines
aircraft on March 18, and are expected to return home in early
April.
</P>
<P>
Before departure, a three-day course will be held to teach the
pilgrims necessary knowledge for the trip.
</P>
<P>
Around 95 percent of the residents in Zanzibar, which has a
population of more than 700,000, are Moslems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
