<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Divers Complete Haul of Golds in Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese divers had their
clean sweep of all six gold medals in the two-day competitions at
the FINA Diving Grand Prix, taking the last two from the men's
10-meter platform and the women's 3-meter springboard here Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
Tian Liang, a 19-year-old diver from Shanxi province, jumped to
the top of the podium with few challenges from his rivals as he
performed all six dives with elegance for a total of 727.90
points, including the game-high 95.2 points from his last routine.
</P>
<P>
"Tonight, he had his best performance in two years. He even
scored 20 more points than that in the World Championships last
January," said coach Zhang Ting.
</P>
<P>
"As many a country failed to send in their top divers for the
event, we encouraged Tian to compete against himself to improve
his own skills," the coach said.
</P>
<P>
Another Chinese teenager Yang Jinghui, 14, took the silver
medal with 579.65 points in his international debut.
</P>
<P>
"Yang is budding star with great potential, and can hopefully
make his impact in the world arena in two years," said judge Xuan
Zengyong.
</P>
<P>
The bronze medal was won by Rueda Eduardo of Mexico with 540.70
points.
</P>
<P>
In the day's last finals of the women's 3-meter springboard,
the 16-year-old Zhang Jing edged over her Chinese compatriot Li
Rongjuan for the top honour, while Michell Chantelle of Australia
took the bronze medal with 510.35 points.
</P>
<P>
"Zhang became the eventual winner due to her tough mentality
and great flexibility, she also enjoyed upperhands in her
jumping," said her coach Liu Henglin.
</P>
<P>
Zhang scored a total of 547.25 points, while Li settled for the
silver with 544.90 points.
</P>
<P>
Less than 60 divers from Australian, Germany, Japan, Mexico and
China competed in the Diving Grand Prix with six gold medals at
stake.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the competition, coaches from Australia, Japan and
Mexico acknowledged that their divers only aimed to accumulate
international experiences instead of cherishing any hope to win
any gold from their Chinese rivals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
