<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Contract Scheme for Sri Lankan Housemaids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Bureau of Foreign
Employment has introduced a new standard employment contract
scheme for women migrant workers who have secured employment
through personal contacts, the bureau said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The scheme requires every Sri Lankan who's going overseas to
work as housemaid to register with the Sri Lankan mission abroad.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said the new employment contract scheme would become
mandatory from March 1.
</P>
<P>
Under the scheme, a foreign sponsor should sign an agreement
with the Sri Lankan mission in the host country to guarantee that
the foreign party would abide by all obligations with regard to
rights of the Sri Lankan working for him or her.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the overseas job seeker is also expected to submit
documents to prove that she has been registered with the
respective mission abroad.
</P>
<P>
Overseas employment has become one of the major sources to
bring in foreign exchanges for Sri Lanka. Remittances sent back by
those working overseas each year could exceed 797 million U.S.
dollars, according to figures given by the bureau.
</P>
<P>
A total of 115,000 Sri Lankans obtained overseas jobs during
the first ten months last year. About 710,000 Sri Lankans are
employed in the Middle East and other Asian regions at present.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
