<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Remains Major Supplier of Cannabis: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Cannabis is illicitly
cultivated in many African countries and Africa remains a major
supplier of cannabis and cannabis resin to Europe and North
America.
</P>
<P>
An annual report distributed here Tuesday said that South
Africa, Morocco and Senegal are large producers of cannabis in
the African continent.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 38.5 tons of cannabis and 65 tons of cannabis resin,
destined for black markets in Europe, were seized by Moroccan law
enforcement services, said the report compiled by the
International Narcotics Control Board (INCB).
</P>
<P>
It noted that large amounts of cannabis were produced in
Western Africa with Senegal reportedly introducing new hybrid
cannabis varieties which had a higher tetrahydrocannabinol
content than the local varieties.
</P>
<P>
African seaports are frequently used by illicit traffickers
for the trans-shipment of cannabis resin from Asia to Europe or
North America, it added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the report said, cannabis is also the main drug of
abuse in Africa and widespread cannabis abuse has been reported
in every subregion in the continent.
</P>
<P>
INCB President, Hamid Ghodse stressed that efforts to reduce
drug abuse worldwide would be less effective if demand reduction
programs are undermined by advocacy for the legalization of
drugs.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the fashion industry coined the term "heroin
chic" and certain pop starts have made statements, saying that
the recreational use of drugs is a normal and acceptable part of
a person's lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
Powerful pressure groups run political campaigns aimed at
legalizing controlled drugs, he said.
</P>
<P>
A special session of the U.N. General Assembly on
international drug control will be held in June this year to
adopt an international declaration on the guiding principles on
drug demand reduction, Ghodse announced in the message. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Growth Rate Fell to 1.7% in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 24 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's economic
growth rate last year was 1.7 percent after a 3.2 percent growth
in 1996, Central Statistical Services (CSS) announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
CSS attributed the decline to the sharp decrease in average
annual growth rate of the agricultural sector from 29.1 percent
in 1996 to -1.0 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
It said the agriculture growth rate was high in 1996 because
the comparison year, 1995, was unusually low. The real annual
growth rate in the GDP of the non-agricultural sector was 1.9
percent for 1997, which was the same as the previous year.
</P>
</TEXT>
