<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Follows Iraq-UN Accord with Concern, Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait said Tuesday it is
following with concern and relief the agreement struck by U.N.
Secretary General Kofi Annan and the Iraqi leadership averting an
U.S. military action in the region.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait Minister of State for Cabinet Affairs Abdelaziz Dakheel
Al-Dakheel said after an extraordinary cabinet meeting Tuesday
that he hopes that Iraq would not go on challenging the
international will and implement the reached accord, adding that
agreement would spare the Iraqi people and region the
repercussions and impacts of military action.
</P>
<P>
He also praised the role of the United Nations in avoiding the
region a military action, saying that the agreement resembles a
victory for the international organization and for its sublime
principles.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-Iraq agreement signed by Annan and Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz Monday morning give a full access of the
U.N. arms inspectors without time limit to all sites in the Iraq
suspected of hiding weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Al-Dakheel also reiterated Kuwait's stand to secure Iraq's
serious and full compliance with its commitments to implement all
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He called for the world community to pressure Iraq on
"releasing Kuwait's prisoners of war and detainees, upholding
threats to neighbors, confidence building and good neighborly
ties, in a manner that leads to establishing peace in the region
and enabling its people to enjoy security and stability."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, most Kuwaiti residents, while breathing a sigh of
relief at the agreement, think the crisis and threat would remain
and may flare up again as long as Saddam Hussein remains in
power. Seven years ago, Kuwait was liberated from the seven-month
Iraqi occupation of the country.
</P>
<P>
However, many of Kuwait's foreign residents who account for 65
percent of the 2.2 million population are relieved after weeks of
tension and fear of Iraqi retaliatory attacks with chemical and
biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
The more than 5000 U.S. and British troops and 12 F-117A
stealth fighter bombers and eight Tornado war planes are expected
to remain in Kuwait for months despite the accord reached, defense
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait Interior Ministry's Director of Public Relations Badr
Al-Saleh also declared Tuesday "the security precautions will be
maintained" in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
