<HEADLINE> Arrangements for HK's Legislature Election on Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Electoral Affairs
Commission has gone halfway through its tasks preparing for the
first legislative Council election of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a speech to the Rotary Club Peninsula here Tuesday,
Justice Woo Kwok-hing, chairman of the commission, said that the
only thing left to be done by the commission before the May
election is overseeing the nominations of candidates, and also
their election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
Woo said the commission has finished delineating geographical
constituencies and its recommendations have been endorsed by the
Chief Executive and tabled at the Provisional Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
Two sets of regulations have been made for a voter registration
exercise, resulting in the publication of provisional registers of
electors and voters for public inspection. More than 180 claims
regarding entries on the registers have been lodged.
</P>
<P>
Another regulation made by the commission containing statutory
provisions for electoral arrangements is being vetted by the
Provisional Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
"We expect that the vetting will be completed within the week.
We shall issue guidelines to explain in simple language the
various aspects of the electoral law and arrangements," he said.
</P>
<P>
"All public views considered reasonable and practicable have
been adopted and reflected in the regulation," he added.
</P>
<P>
Woo said the commission has appointed four Nominations Advisory
Committees to give legal advice to prospective candidates if they
have doubts about their eligibility to run for the April subsector
elections or the May general elections.
</P>
<P>
Turning to arrangements on the polling day, Woo said that a
combined polling arrangement would be adopted.
</P>
<P>
"All electors, except the 800 members of the Election
Committee, may cast all their votes at a polling station near
their homes on May 24," he said.
</P>
<P>
Woo appealed to the audience to participate in the elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
