<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets Irish Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said
that it is wise for the European Union (EU) not to present an
anti-China bill this year and China appreciates the EU's attitude
toward strengthening dialogue and cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
Li made the remark in a meeting with Irish Foreign Minister
David Andrews who arrived here this morning for a four-day
official visit to China as guest of Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China has always attached importance to its
relations with the EU which is an important group in a
multi-polarized world. The two sides share common interests in
safeguarding world peace and promoting common development, he
added.
</P>
<P>
China will -- on the basis of mutual respect, equality and
reciprocity -- make its efforts to further its relations with all
EU member countries including Ireland, and expand cooperation in
various fields between the two sides, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Andrews recalled his visit to China as head of a football team
in 1976 when China was undergoing difficulties, saying that he has
found that great changes have taken place in China in the past 22
years.
</P>
<P>
He said his current visit here is aimed at revealing the
sincere hopes of the new Irish government to further its friendly
relations with China, and informing China of an important decision
made by the just-concluded council meeting of EU foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
Andrews told Li that the council agreed that neither the
presidency nor member states should table or co-sponsor a draft
resolution against China at the next session of the
U.N. Commission on Human Rights, adding EU members' satisfaction
with the encouraging results acquired during dialogues between the
EU and China on human rights, which Li expressed his appreciation.
</P>
<P>
Li said that he and the former Irish Prime Minister agreed to
further bilateral relations in their meeting in Rome during the
World Food Summit in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Andrews' current visit to China as the first cabinet member of
the new Irish government indicates the significance the Irish
government attaches to the development of bilateral relations, Li
said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that since China and Ireland established
diplomatic ties in 1979, the two sides have conducted fruitful
cooperation in politics, economy and trade, science and
technology, and culture, and bilateral trade volume has increased
steadily.
</P>
<P>
China welcomes more cooperation between enterprises of the two
countries, and the Chinese government will give its due support
and encouragement, Li said.  
</P>
