<HEADLINE> Yemeni Daily Hails Iraq-UN Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- A Yemeni government-run
newspaper on Tuesday hailed as a triumph of the civilized world
the agreement on arms inspections reached between Iraq and the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The agreement embodies a peaceful solution to the standoff
between Iraq and the U.N. Special Commission charged with
overseeing the elimination of Iraq's weapons of mass destruction,
the Al-Thawra said in an editorial.
</P>
<P>
It implies a victory of the international legitimacy and world
peace because a diplomatic solution to the Iraqi crisis is a gain
for all the members of the international community, the paper
added.
</P>
<P>
After two days of intense talks, U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz signed the
agreement on Monday, under which Iraq will open all sites to
U.N. inspection.
</P>
<P>
Al-Thawra stressed that political and diplomatic efforts are
ideal means and have proved successful in resolving international
disputes, however complicated and difficult they may be.
</P>
<P>
The Iraq-U.N. agreement will spare the Middle East a disaster,
and meet the legitimate demands of the concerned parties, it added.
</P>
<P>
The United States has vowed that it would attack Iraq if
diplomacy failed to persuade Iraqi President Saddam Hussein to
back down from the decision to bar the arms inspectors from
entering presidential sites.
</P>
<P>
The paper called on the U.N. to lift, as soon as Iraq has fully
complied with the relevant U.N. resolutions, the economic
sanctions imposed on Iraq in 1990 after its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
</TEXT>
