<HEADLINE> Seventh China-Japan Friendship Exchange Meeting Held in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The biannual China-Japan
Friendship Exchange Meeting was held here today.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting was sponsored by the China-Japan Friendship
Association (CJFA) and the Japan-China Friendship Association
(JCFA). Some 45 Chinese and 79 Japanese participants, as well as
government officials and activists from the two countries,
attended the opening ceremony this morning.
</P>
<P>
Qi Huanyuan, president of the Chinese People's Association for
Friendship with Foreign Countries, said in his opening speech that
the year 1998, which marks the 20th anniversary of the signing of
Sino-Japanese Treaty of Peace and Friendship, could be considered
a pivotal point in the China-Japan ties.
</P>
<P>
He urged participants to make joint efforts to build friendly
and cooperative Sino-Japanese relations for the 21st
century in line with promoting traditions and expanding exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Ikuo Hirayama, president of the JCFA, sent a greeting to those
attending the meeting, urging non-governmental bodies
in the two countries to make sincere efforts and take concrete
measures for the future Japan-China relationship.
</P>
<P>
Chen Yongchang, vice-president of the CJFA, and Masao Shimizu,
vice-president of the JCFA, spoke in the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The event, already held six times, was first initiated by Liao
Chengzhi, the late president of the CJFA, and the former JCFA
President Tokuma Utsunomiya in 1983. 
</P>
