<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nearly 9,400 Iraqis Die in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 7,000 Iraqi children
below 5 and about 2,400 elderly died last month due to diseases
partly caused by harsh international economic sanctions, the Iraqi
News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to an Iraqi Health Ministry report, the children
mainly died of diarrhea, pleurisy and malnutrition, while the
elderly died of hypertension, diabetes and tumors.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the deaths to the lack of food and
medicine owing to the sanctions imposed on Iraq by the United
Nations in 1990 after Iraqi troops' invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. embargo bars Iraq from exporting oil, the main revenue
earner. In December, 1996, the U.N. allowed Iraq to sell 2 billion
U.S. dollars worth of oil every six months under an oil-for-food
deal, to buy food and medicine, but the plan can hardly meet the
needs.
</P>
<P>
Previous statistics of the Iraqi ministry showed that more than
1.5 million Iraqis, mostly children and elderly, have died since
the sanctions began.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi report said that only 389 children and 277 elderly
died in January, 1989. 
</P>
</TEXT>
