<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Restores Pre-Shipment Inspection on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has suspended the abolition
of pre-shipment inspection on imports it announced earlier this year,
in a fresh effort to check abuses of the liberailized economic
policies.
</P>
<P>
Disclosing the new policy decision in the captal Abuja on Monday,
Finance Minister Anthony Ani said that all goods, irrespective of
their ports of origin, should continue to undergo pre-shipment
inspection.
</P>
<P>
The government earlier abolished pre-shipment inspection on
imported goods from Australia, Bangladesh, Cyprus, Britain, Hong
Kong, Indonesia, Ireland, Japan, Malaysia, New Zealand, Pakistan,
China, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and all countries in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Probably to comfort foreign trade businessmen, Ani also announced
that the government will bear the cost of pre-shipment inspection
services this time.
</P>
<P>
The restoration of the services, according to Ani, was informed by
the fact that some unscrupulous Nigerians and their foreign
collaborators had taken advantage of the government's good intention
toward facilitating clearance of goods to perpetrate capital flight.
</P>
<P>
They just forged papers to get foreign exchange from the
government-control exchange market at a rate a one U.S.Dollar to 75
Naira and sold at non-official market for 84 Naira, making easy money.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the government had to supply 800 million dollars to
meet the "steep rise" in the demand at the official foreign exchange
market during the first four or five weeking biddings this year,
according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
"It is most unacceptable. The government has, therefore, decided that
with effect from now, we have to go back to pre-shipment inspection,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government has also issued fresh guidelines for the
official exchange market known as autonomous foreign exchange market
(AFEM), where the Central Bank sells exchange to selected commercial
banks through a weekly bidding.
</P>
<P>
The fresh move is aimed to curb foreign exchange abuses being
perpetrated by slippery businessmen, dealers and bankers.
</P>
<P>
As part of the measures, all bills of collection, which are
arrangements whereby importers are given a grace period of few months
before funding their imports, will be funded through free fund market
instead of through AFEM.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate at free fund market is higher than that at AFEM.
</P>
<P>
According to analysts, tightening exchange control might help
protect the country's foreign exchange reserve and curb unscrupulous
businessmen to make easy money by taking advantage of the liberalized
policy environment.
</P>
<P>
However, the re-introduction of the pre-shipment inspection
services is expected to invite complaining from genuine importers and
exporters although the government has promised to bear the cost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0161 </DOCNO>
