<HEADLINE> Fish Export Becomes Second Foreign Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's fish export has
become the country's second foreign exchange earner next to
coffee, according to Henry Kajura, Ugandan Minister of Trade and
Industry.
</P>
<P>
The minister told a one-day workshop on fish industry that the
foreign exchange earned by fish export increased from 1.2 billion
Uganda Shillings (some 1.2 million U.S. Dollars) in 1991 to 39
billion Shillings (some 39 million Dollars) in 1997, The Monitor
newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, Kajura expressed concerns about a sustainable
development of the industry due to the coverage of lake surface
by water hyacinth and the dumping of industrial waste into the
lake.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicated reduced catches in all major lakes,
the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out the suffocating effect of commercial
fishing on traditional fishermen. The small scale fishing
industry is the main economic activity in the areas adjacent to
Lake Victoria and Lake Kiyoga in the central part of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
