<HEADLINE> China Classification Society Registers More Ships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The China Classification
Society (CCS) under the Ministry of Communications had registered
a total of 1,904 ships, with a total capacity of 15.24 million
tons, by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The society registered 36 ships, with a total capacity of
520,000 tons, in 1997 alone, according CCS director Xie Jinhai.
</P>
<P>
Registration enables vessels to enjoy lower premiums for
ocean shipping and the CCS examines vessels at regular
intervals. The CCS is recognized as one of the world's most
prestigious ship registration societies.
</P>
<P>
CCS also registered 116 types of equipment for domestic vessels
and 175 types of foreign maritime equipment during 1997.
</P>
<P>
The ISM Code system was implemented nationwide in 1997, with
more than 400 enterprises having since passed CCS ISO9000
assessments, according to Xie. 
</P>
