<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Fund Industry Records Modest Growth in 1997: Lord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Despite the financial crisis
in the fourth quarter of 1997, Hong Kong's fund management
industry managed to register modest growth for the full year, the
Hong Kong Investment Funds Association (HKIFA) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
As at the end of December 1997, HKIFA members managed 772
authorized unit trusts and mutual funds, representing total assets
of 58.5 billion U.S. dollars. This compared with 723 funds and
41.5 billion U.S. dollars of assets a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the development of the fund industry, Peter Lord,
chairman of the HKIFA, said: "Despite the Asian maelstrom in the
fourth quarter of 1997, the fund industry saw a modest growth for
the full year and the industry continues to maintain its balanced
and diversified characteristics."
</P>
<P>
"The wider distribution of unit trusts by banks, combined with
higher levels of education and financial awareness among the
public, helped the industry both to grow and to weather the
storms," said Lord.
</P>
<P>
But he pointed out the industry was not immune from the
regional crisis. "The crisis, which has dampened the general
investment sentiment, left the fund industry with a substantial
drop in gross sales, and net outflows in most of the equity
sectors in the fourth quarter."
</P>
<P>
However, the impact is likely not to be as severe or as
extensive as that felt in certain other sectors within the
financial industry.
</P>
<P>
As for the prospects of the next couple of months, Lord said,
"While investment sentiment has shown some improvement, we don't
envisage a massive influx of new money in the immediate future."
</P>
<P>
"One reason is that there are still uncertainties over the
outcome of the Asian financial crisis. Also, as interest rates
stay high and the amount required to service mortgage loans has
grown faster than wage levels, inflows will remain subdued in the
short-term."
</P>
<P>
Over the longer term, Lord believed that the growth in the unit
trust industry would be bolstered by the changes in the
demographic profiles of the local population.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's population is relatively young with 63 percent
being under 30 years of age. In the next five or ten years, there
is a large group of well educated, young consumers moving through
their financial establishment phase and they will be more likely
to invest in unit trusts and other forms of equity-related assets,
Lord said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Wraps up One-Two in Men's 1m Springboard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese divers wrapped up
a one-two finish in the men's one-meter springboard finals at the
1998 FINA Diving Grand Prix here Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Gong Ming, a Beijing native, led the rest of the field from his
first dive en route to winning the gold medal by a convincing
margin with 407.45 points, beating compatriot Wang Kenan to second
with 379.70.
</P>
<P>
Robert Newbery of Australia finished third with 338.75 points.
</P>
<P>
"Gong excuted every dive excellently, and I hope he can make
steady progresses in the future as he failed to reap any medal in
the National Games last October," said his coach at the poolside.
</P>
<P>
Previously, the 20-year-old Gong had no brilliant titles to his
credit, but he was strong in the technical merits and hopefully
would be a budding star in China in the springboard, said judge
Xuan Zengyong. 
</P>
