<HEADLINE> Mongolia to Absorb More Foreign Investment in Oil, Mining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Mongolian Prime Minister
Mendsaikhan Enkhsaikhan said Tuesday that Mongolia is taking
measures to absorb more foreign investment in oil and mining
industry.
</P>
<P>
Enkhsaikhan told Xinhua that these measures include improvement
of relevant rules and regulations on exploitation, simplifying
procedures on negotiations and agreement signing, and tax
exempting for foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
In the past three months, he noted, Mongolia reached five
agreements with foreign companies on the distribution of oil
products.
</P>
<P>
Beginning to use foreign investment in 1993, he said,
Mongolia's oil industry is now exporting to China to open new
field for bilateral economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Enkhsaikhan recalled that Mongolia's industrial output
increased by 4.4 percent in 1997 and that of the mining sector
went up by as high as 17.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
A new mining law, which came into effect last July, provides
additional legal protection to foreign companies that are licensed
to explore on 20 percent of Mongolia's land, Enkhsaikhan
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
