<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets Japanese News Service President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin said
here today that from now until the turn of the century is a
crucial period for furthering Sino-Japanese relations into the
21st century and an important period for the two countries to
inherit the past and usher in the future.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made his remarks at a meeting with Yashuhiko Inukai,
president of Japan's Kyodo News Service.
</P>
<P>
This year marks the 20th anniversary of the signing of the
Sino-Japan treaty of peace and friendship and last year was the
25th anniversary of the normalization of the relations between the
countries. At this juncture, he said, China and Japan should value
and treasure the existing good bilateral ties and make concerted
efforts to help consolidate and advance the long-term, stable and
good-neighborly relations through learning from past experiences
and lessons, and taking advantage of the current situation.
</P>
<P>
Jiang described the bilateral relations as generally good since
the normalization 26 years ago, featured by yielding in various
fields through exchanges and cooperation. Though there have been
twists and turns, relevant issues have been handled properly in
time because of the joint efforts of both governments, he said.
</P>
<P>
China and Japan are both big Asian countries, he
noted. Long-term friendship and cooperation between the two
countries benefit the two peoples and will exert an important
impact on the peace and stability of the world.
</P>
<P>
Yashuhiko said he was pleased to meet with the president. The
successful convening of the 15th National Congress of the Chinese
Communist Party and the upcoming first session of the Ninth
National People's Congress would further advance China's social
and economic development and enable China to usher in the 21st
century, he added.
</P>
<P>
Guo Chaoren, president of the Xinhua News Agency, was present
at the meeting. The Kyodo News Service delegation is here as
guests of Xinhua.  
</P>
</TEXT>
