<HEADLINE> Profile: Official for Border Area Development Elected NPC Deputy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Mayor Jin Shuoren of
Hunchun city in northeast China's Jilin Province is a newly
elected deputy to the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), which
will be held in Beijing early March.
</P>
<P>
"The decisive factor for my election lies in the strategic
position of Hunchun, a key for the development of the Tumen River
which requires the combined efforts of the U.N. Development
Program and several Asian countries," said Jin, 44.
</P>
<P>
"During the NPC session, I will forward the opinions of local
people and appeal to the country for accelerating the pace of
international cooperation in terms of the Tumen River's
development," he added.
</P>
<P>
Jin, of Korean origin, graduated from the Department of
Political Sciences at Yanbian University. He obtained a master's
degree from Jilin University in 1994 and is pursuing a doctoral
degree in world economy. He took up the post of city mayor in
January of 1996.
</P>
<P>
He has succeeded in increasing the industrial output of his
city from 230 million yuan to 440 million yuan in two
years. An export-oriented economy, covering the fields of finance,
foreign trade, tourism, real estate and high-technology, has taken
shape at a state-listed development zone on the border between
Hunchun and Russia and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea
(DPRK).
</P>
<P>
To facilitate the development of the Tumen River area, Hunchun
is building a 39-kilometer highway leading to Juanhe City on the
Sino-Korean border and speeding construction of a railway line
between China and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Outlining major steps for the Tumen River area's development,
Jin said that his city would carry out technological upgrading of
a local power plant, improve facilities at Juanhe Port, build a
reservoir at Laolongkou and open sea and land outlets to the
Republic of Korea and the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
In his leisure time, Jin is busy preparing for his doctoral
thesis on market economies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
