<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Passengers, Goods Traffic Soar in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 24 (Xinhua) -- A total of 52.3 million
passengers and 452 million tons of cargo were transported to and
from Shanghai in 1997, rises of 2.1 percent and 0.3 percent over
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Of the total passengers, the largest number -- 27.7 million --
travelled by train, a slight drop from the 1996 figure, and 14.5
million travelled by road, up 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
More than 6.7 million passengers entered and left the city by
air, up 8.2 percent, and 3.2 million did so by water, down 22.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
Cargo transported to and from the city by motor vehicle
accounted for the largest volume, reaching nearly 260 million
tons, up 3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, goods transported by rail and water dropped 6.4
percent and 3.1 percent, respectively, to reach 58 million tons
and nearly 134 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Last year the handling capacity of local ports reached nearly
164 million tons, the same level as 1996.
</P>
<P>
And the remaining 480,000 tons of goods were transported by
air, a 16.7 percent rise from the 1996 figure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
