<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Federation to Help Laid-off Women Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The All China Women's
Federation will work to help more laid-off women to find new jobs
and more rural women to rise above the poverty line this year.
</P>
<P>
The federation plans to set up more re-employment training
bases across the country for laid-off women workers, said Zhang
Shiping, a federation official.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that local women's unions across the country will
also found their own economic entities to provide jobs for
unemployed women.
</P>
<P>
The women are also advised to find jobs in the service industry
and the non-public sector, whose development is encouraged under
the guidelines of the 15th National Congress of the Communist
Party of China, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
China's has more than 10 million laid-off workers, and 20
million more are expected to become redundant as state-owned
enterprises streamline their workforce to improve efficiency. The
majority of laid-off workers are women.
</P>
<P>
During the last two years, the women's federation has set up
employment information centers in 25 cities, trained one million
laid-off women and helped more than 300,000 of them find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
In the countryside, the federation will get more rural women to
learn and use new farming technology, especially those in ethnic
minority and remote areas, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
China's impoverished was estimated at 50 million last year. The
All China Women's Federation plans to help one million rural women
out of poverty in the 1996-2000 period.
</P>
<P>
With the March 8 International Working Women's Day approaching,
the federation has commended 280 individuals and 22 groups for
their contribution to the improvement of women's status as well as
social progress.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
