<HEADLINE> Zambia Revenue Authority Vows to Meet Revenue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Zambia Revenue Authority
(ZRA) has vowed to meet this year's revenue target by tightening
loose ends and improving operations.
</P>
<P>
Financial Mail Tuesday quoted ZRA Chairman Patrick Chiumya as
telling the local weekly newspaper that ZRA will go ahead and
tighten loose ends to ensure the targeted revenue from local
resources of 1178.75 billion Kwacha (about 845 million U.S.
Dollars) is achieved.
</P>
<P>
Loopholes such as smuggling will be sealed through deployment
of the fast team patrols and increasing the number of employees
to curb smuggling, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Zambia Association of Manufacturers and the Zambia
Association of Chambers of Commerce and Industry have expressed
their concern that smuggling is on the increase while other
observers feel that even the hiked duty on second hand clothes
will increase smuggling, the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
There has been an outcry from various sections of the
community charging that hiked duty on the imports of second-hand
clothes will hurt the poor and civil servants.
</P>
<P>
But Chiumya noted that smuggling will be reduced by effecting
various measures.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Ronald Penza announced in his budget at the
end of last month the increased duty on the second hand clothes.
</P>
<P>
This year's total revenue stands at about 1,300 million
Dollars, of which 65 percent will come from the domestic revenue.
</P>
</TEXT>
