<HEADLINE> Service Trades on Rise in North China Port City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, February 24 (Xinhua) -- North China's port city of
Tianjin pumped 20.71 billion yuan into the burgeoning tertiary
industry in 1997, which has become a major driving force in local
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The investment indicates a 25.8-percent rise over 1996,
according to the municipal Statistical Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the sector has also become a major focus of overseas
investors.
</P>
<P>
The added value of tertiary industry for Tianjin in 1997
amounted to 52.19 billion yuan, or 42.1 percent of the city's GDP.
</P>
<P>
The service industry -- which includes communications, posts
and telecommunications, public utilities construction and finance
-- outpaced the manufacturing sector by 10.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Real estate, whose turnover rose by 18.2 percent last year over
1996, led the tertiary sector.
</P>
<P>
Rapid growth of its tertiary industry will help fortify
Tianjin's status as the center in the dynamic Bohai Rim. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
