<HEADLINE> Mandela Relieved at U.N.-Iraq Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 24 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela Tuesday expressed relief at the apparent
diplomatic solution to the standoff in Baghdad over United
Nations weapons inspections following Monday's agreement between
Iraq and UN chief Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his Cape Town residence, Mandela said he had not
yet seen the details of the agreement, but had read in the
newspapers that United States President Bill Clinton appeared to
be happy with it and would support it.
</P>
<P>
Although it was premature to comment on the agreement before
he had seen the text, Mandela said it was a great relief to see
an improvement on the issue, South African Press Association
reported.
</P>
<P>
"It was of great concern, the threat to strike, because we
knew it's not to hit any military target -- it's going to kill
children, women, the aged: very innocent people, and that is
something that we cannot tolerate," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very happy that it does appear that the tension that was
building up is now going to be eliminated," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said his government supported diplomatic solutions.
</P>
<P>
"We are against any form of violence no matter by whom it is
caused. We went out of our way in our own country to avoid
violence and we think the entire world should do that," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
