<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Crude Oil Production up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Africa's top oil producer
Nigeria has seen its crude oil production up by 10,000 barrels a
day following the operation of two new oil fields.
</P>
<P>
The new oil fields, located at Ogbotobo and Agbaya in the
Delta State in the south, began production last month from a
total of seven wells, media reports said.
</P>
<P>
The new oil fields are operated by the Shell Petroleum
Development Company, a join venture between the world oil giant
Shell and the Nigeria National Petroleum Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Shell officials were quoted as saying that the new fields have
raised the joint venture's output to 930,000 barrels a day, or 43
percent of Nigeria's total production of 2.175 million barrels a
day.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, the new fields' production will rise to
26,000 barrels a day, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
They disclosed that exploration drilling in the Gongola basin
in northeast Nigeria will begin this year, as a seismic survey of
the area has been finished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
