<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Biopiracy of Indian Plants Continues: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Biopiracy of Indian plants
is continuing unabated by developed countries, said a report
available here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A fact-sheet, prepared by India's Research Foundation for
Science, Technology and Ecology, lists 22 medicinal and
agricultural plants that have been patented by American and
European countries. Apart from Neem and Turmeric, a number of
other Indian plants such as Mustard, Black Pepper, Castor and
Cumin, etc., have been patented by some developed countries.
</P>
<P>
There are about 100 plants which have already been patented by
Americans.
</P>
<P>
The Hindu said Tuesday in its editorial that "What is baffling
is that the U.S. firm has obtained the patent when it cannot by
any means claim Basmati (rice) as its invention or a registered
brand. Basmati is grown in parts of northern India and both India
and Pakistan have a virtual monopoly of this strain in the world
market."
</P>
<P>
"The patent issue underscores the threat of biopiracy by
foreign firms under the new dispensation of globalization," it
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
