<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Only One Percent Nigerian School Age Kids Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Only one percent of the school
age children in Nigeria meet the World Health Organization (WHO)
minimum nutritional standard, a leading newspaper here reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has 15 million children in primary schools, with three
million of them not going to school because of socio-economic
problems, particularly lack of funds.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 10 percent of them suffer learning disability, the
Guardian reported, quoting Taoheed Adedoja, provost of the
Federal College of Education.
</P>
<P>
The professor described the disability as "inability to cope
with the acquisition of knowledge within one's age range".
</P>
<P>
The dean listed poor learning environment, distractions, poor
nutrition and lack of facilities as some of contributing factors
to the disability.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the minimum quantity of food to be consumed
should be one egg for four children, but it is now for 40
children.
</P>
<P>
"The situation has become compounded because of the
socio-economic problems and as a result of the poor nutrition,
more children are being handicapped," Adedoja said.
</P>
<P>
The situation is worrisome in the eastern part of the country
where there is high rate of dropout because they do not see the
utility in education for self-development, the dean added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
