<HEADLINE> Share Prices Close Higher on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Share prices closed higher
on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials
Index (STII) increased by 9.84 points to close at 1561.75 points
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Market players said that the stock prices ended higher in
cautious trading ahead of the government's release of the 1998-99
budget on Friday. The budget was not expected to unveil any
positive surprises, they said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that players were also eyeing the 1997 full-year
survey of the Singapore economy and forecast for 1998 Gross
Domestic Product, which will be released early on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume increased to 561.35 million units,
valued at 492.47 million Singapore dollars (about 300.29 million
U.S. dollars). Advances overwhelmed declines by 279 to 79, while
253 other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
MBf Capital was the most actively traded counter as it
registered a turnover of 53.33 million units. It was followed by
Ber Group which had 23.49 million shares traded. Renong Bhd was
next with 23.46 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
NBT led the gainers of the day as it rose by 74 cents to finish
at 4.44 Singapore dollars. City Developments Warrant98 increased
by 50 cents to end at 4.2 Singapore dollars. Elec picked up by 40
cents to close at 6.3 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, the Singapore Airlines (SIA) Foreign was the
biggest loser as it declined by 40 cents to end at 12.1 Singapore
dollars. F&AMP;N and OCBC (Overseas Chinese Banking Corporation)
Foreign each fell by 25 cents to close at 7.35 and 9.3 Singapore
dollars respectively, while Boustd S was 22 cents lower finishing
at 1.73 Singapore dollars. 
</P>
