<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China Province Set to Boost Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, February 24 (Xinhua) -- North China's Hebei
province has listed agriculture top priority on its economic
development agenda and has vowed to give a major shot in the arm
of high-yielding agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural province will also redouble efforts to achieve
steady growth in both agro-produces and farmers' incomes.
</P>
<P>
Located in the center of the north China Plain, Hebei is one of
the country's leading agricultural producer, especially in wheat,
fruits, edible oil and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
Apart from meeting the needs of its 64 million people, Hebei
provides quality wheat and corn to provinces in south and
northwest China, and large amounts of meat, eggs, milk and
vegetables to Beijing and Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Grain output in Hebei totalled 27.5 million tons in 1997, one
of two all-time highs in the province's history, while net per
capita income of local farmers grew 8,6 percent to reach 2,286
yuan.
</P>
<P>
Partly stimulated by demand from the country's capital,
Beijing, which it surrounds, Hebei has expanded its vegetable
acreage to 800,000 ha, 140,000 ha of which are vinyl-sheeted.
</P>
<P>
The province is also making great efforts to guarantee funds
for agricultural purposes and improve water conservancy
facilities. It expects to increase its area of irrigated land by
about 380,000 ha this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
