<HEADLINE> EU's Decision Not to Table Draft Resolution Against China Welcomed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government today
extended its welcome to a decision made by the European Union (EU)
not to table any draft resolution against China at this year's
session of the United Nations (UN) Human Rights Commission.
</P>
<P>
The remark came from Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao at
today's regular news conference when commenting on such a decision
made during the EU foreign ministers' meeting Monday that neither
the EU president nor any of the EU members will table or jointly
sign any draft resolution against China at this year's session of
the UN Human Rights Commission.
</P>
<P>
This has fully demonstrated that dialogue and cooperation on
human rights issues on the basis of equality and mutual respect
constitute the correct way to enhance mutual understanding and
narrow differences, which, he noted, has become a common
understanding of an increasing number of countries.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that this decision made by the EU will further
promote the relations between China and the EU and between China
and the EU members, including the dialogue and cooperation between
the two sides in the field of human rights," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
