<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 08:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> mee022405hke - Iran Welcomes EU Decision to Resume Contacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi here Tuesday voiced Tehran's welcome to the decision of
the European Union (EU) to resume ministerial contacts with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions at the opening session of the 8th Persian
Gulf seminar, Kharrazi said the EU decision indicated European
countries have a better understanding about the developments and
situation in Iran.
</P>
<P>
"We have announced our readiness to expand relations with
other countries on the basis of mutual respect and mutual
interest," he said. However, he stressed that Iran opposes any
unilateral decisions on others.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said Iran welcomes any cooperation and dialogue bassed
on mutual respect and interest, which he said could resolve many
international issues.
</P>
<P>
The EU decided Monday to end the 10-month-old freeze on
senior-level contacts with Iran to "respond positively" to recent
"encouraging" developments in Iran and its interest in more
constructive relations.
</P>
<P>
The 15 EU foreign ministers called for an EU-Iran dialogue on
terrorism, the production of weapons of mass destruction, the
death sentence imposed by Iran's late spiritual leader Ayatollah
Khomenei on the British writer Salman Rushdie for his
"blasphemous" novel, and the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Iran's willingness to address these concerns would greatly
enhance the success of the dialogue and Iran's reintegration into
the international community," the communique said.
</P>
<P>
The EU suspended its ministerial contacts and its "critical
dialogue" with Iran last April after a German court accused
Iranian leaders of sponsoring a terrorist assassination of four
Iranian Kurdish rebel leaders in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
An ease of tension appeared last November when the EU sent
their envoys back to Tehran in response to Iran's new, moderate
President Mohammad Khatami's appeal for friendly relations with
the outside world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
