<HEADLINE> S. Leonean President Visits Nigeria on Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Deposed Sierra Leonean
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah has arrived in Abuja, capital of
Nigeria, for a two-day working visit, press reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah, who flew into Abuja from Conakry, Guinea, where he has
lived in exile after his ousting in a coup last May, was received
by Nigeria's Head of State General Sani Abacha at the airport
Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders then went into closed-door deliberations in
the State House, where they are believed to have discussed the
issue of Kabbah's return to power, reportedly to take place later
this week.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the State House are quoted as saying that the
meeting was necessitated by the fact that General Abacha is the
current chairman of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS), whose peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG flushed out
the military junta in Freetown about a fortnight ago.
</P>
<P>
Following the sack of the junta, Kabbah has advised his
countrymen to remain calm and to return to their normal business,
while preparing for a comeback from Conakry.
</P>
<P>
Currently, ECOMOG is in firm control of the capital Freetown
and Bo, the second largest city in Sierra Leone, but some other
major towns are still under the control of forces loyal to the
junta.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the whereabouts of the junta leader Johnny Paul
Koroma still remains unknown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
