<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Pest Threatening Africa's Citrus Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Scientists have identified a
new insect pest that poses serious threat to citrus plants in
eastern and southern Africa, the East African Standard newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Infestations of the citrus woolly white fly, also known as
Aleurothrixus floccosus, are becoming wide-spread especially in
central and western Kenya, Uganda, northern Tanzania, Zanzibar,
and central and southern Malawi, said the report.
</P>
<P>
"Although the insect usually target citrus trees, in Africa it
has also been reported on coffee, guava, mango and eggplant," the
report said.
</P>
<P>
However, the citrus woolly white fly has not yet created havoc
in farming communities in Africa, according to the Agroforestry
Today, a journal issued by the Nairobi-based International Center
for Research in Agroforesty (ICRAF).
</P>
<P>
It became the most devastating citrus pest of the
Mediterranean in mid-1970s, when the economy of entire regions
depends on citrus production.
</P>
<P>
Research findings show that the citrus woolly white fly causes
damage by feeding on leaves and fruits, resulting in partial
defoliation, mottled, small fruits and generally weakened trees.
</P>
<P>
Considered more serious, however, is the insect's copious
production of honeydew.
</P>
<P>
It has been observed that these heavy deposits and subsequent
growth of sooty would impede assimilation process of leaves and
make pruning and fruit picking difficult.
</P>
<P>
So far the only solution is to use exotic parasitoids to kill
the pest, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The insects live on the young flush (the new growth of leafy
shoots) of citrus, where adults lay their eggs on the lower
surface of the leaves.
</P>
<P>
"The nymphs, permanently attached to the leaf surface, feed on
the sap of the plant. During development, they produce fine
threads of a waxy substance, which cover the entire colony of the
immature white flies like cotton wool -- hence the name," said the
journal.
</P>
<P>
The adult woolly white fly measures less than 0.5 mm long and
cannot be easily distinguished from other white flies such as the
cotton white fly. But the pest is easily identified in its
immature stages by its colonies on the lower leaf surfaces of
citrus trees.
</P>
<P>
The total development time of the insect in the tropics is
about one month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0215 </DOCNO>
