<HEADLINE> Bulgaria to Promote Animal Husbandry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria has produced a
development plan to spend 280 billion leva (about 156 million
U.S. dollars) between 1998-2001 to restore and promote its animal
husbandry, a senior official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Minister Ventsislav Varbanov said that part of the
money will come from Bulgaria's "agriculture fund" and the rest from
the World Bank loans and funds of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria's animal husbandry has suffered greatly from the
nation's unstable economical situation since 1989. A traditionally
agrarian country, Bulgaria has to import meats from the United
States and Brazil for domestic consumption at high cost.
</P>
<P>
Even the plan, a product of efforts of 35 Bulgarian experts of
months, is fully carried out, Bulgaria's animal husbandry
production level in 2001 is still expected to be far below that of
1989. 
</P>
</TEXT>
