<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 09:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Opposes Foreign Military Presence in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 24 (Xinhua) - Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi here Tuesday restated Tehran's opposition to any foreign
military presence in the Persian Gulf, stressing that security in
the region would only be maintained through regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session of the 8th Persian Gulf
seminar, Kharrazi said that security in the Gulf region could not
be "imported" and "neither the importation and accumulation of
huge arsenal of weapons will help improve security situation."
</P>
<P>
He said that the presence of forces from outside of the region
would not help strengthen regional security but would serve as
an element of tension.
</P>
<P>
"Existence of crises provides an excuse for the presence of
these forces," he said, "their presence will turn the region
into a military barrack, cause greater instability... and in
the long run impede political, social and economical development
of the countries in the region."
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi reiterated that Iran seeks peace, stability and
security in the Gulf, saying that "nothing is more important
for Iran in the pursuit of its foreign policy than to
consolidate stability and security in the Persian Gulf."
</P>
<P>
He said that the ongoing visit of Chairman of Iran's
State Expediency Council and former Iranian President Hashemi
Rafsanjani to Saudi Arabia "is a clear indication of friendly
relationships between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
"We have also reached out to other countries in the
region in a bid to further improve our bilateral cooperation,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani left here Saturday for a ten-day official visit
to Saudi Arabia in an aim to improve relations between the
two important states in the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi stressed that disputes and misunderstandings can and
must be resolved through peaceful means, without resorting to
coercive measures, stating that confidence building should be
accorded high priority and new innovative approaches should be
explored.
</P>
<P>
"I believe dialogue is the only way to go" the Iranian
foreign minister said, dialogue and exchange of ideas and
views can form the constituent parts of a desirable security
system in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed regret that Iraq has suffered in the
recent years under the U.N. sanctions following the Gulf war
in 1991, hoping that the recent Iraqi crisis would be
resolved in a peaceful manner through a more rational policy
by the Iraqi leaders and good offices of the U.N. Security
General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
Annan and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz Monday
signed a document over the U.N.-Iraq standoff over arms
inspection, averting a U.S. military strike on the country.
</P>
<P>
The two-day seminar of "regional approaches in the Persian
Gulf" will discuss the latest developments in the region,
particularly the recent Iraqi crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
