<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Hezbollah Calls for Hebrew TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's Hezbollah has
suggested the government set up a satellite television station
that beams programs in Hebrew to the Israeli public, the local Daily
Star newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Such a TV station is aimed at reaping the heated debate in
Israel over the future of its occupation of south Lebanon,
Hezbollah's press chief Nayef Krayem said on Monday at a lunch
organized for the local media.
</P>
<P>
It will serve to increase the number of Israelis that object to
the occupation and support a withdrawal of troops, he said.
</P>
<P>
If approved, the station will be government-run, he said,
adding the Hezbollah, or Party of God, is ready to help, because
it has "several members fluent in Hebrew."
</P>
<P>
He said it would be an example that media can play a role in
supporting resistance against Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to meet with Lebanese Information Minister
Bassem Al-Sabaa Tuesday to officially present the suggestion.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah is spearheading an anti-Israeli
occupation campaign, militarily and psychologically, in an effort
to oust 2,500 Israeli occupation troops from south Lebanon.
</P>
</TEXT>
