<HEADLINE> East African Countries to Cooperate in Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Uganda, Kenya and Tanzania
will Cooperate in training their army troops, Ugandan State
Minister for Foreign Affairs Rebecca Kadaga has said.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with the visiting British Parliament
International Development Committee (IDC) delegation on Monday,
the Ugandan minister of state talked of the east African
coopeation in troops training and noted that there is " no ulterior
motive" in the joint training program.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions from the visitors about east African
cooperation, Kadaga said a memorandum of association is due to be
signed during the east African cooperation meeting due to be held
on March 10 in Arusha, Tanzania. Modalities will be worked out
on how to carry out the exercise, she explained.
</P>
<P>
She denied the allegation that Uganda was boosted by the U.S.
against Sudan. ''We are in the world camp against terrorism and
fundamentalism, and not on the American camp against Sudan,'' she
added.
</P>
<P>
IDC is a all-party committee of the House of Commons which
monitors the work of the British government's Department for
International Development which is responsible for Britain's
overseas development program. The 10-member IDC delegation
started its visit to the country since last friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
