<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
closed higher Tuesday in Sydney following strong local
institutional buying and the ANZ Banking Group's announcement that
it would cut 1,700 jobs.
</P>
<P>
Investors interpreted the redundancies as indicating further
staff losses among other banks in the future, which pushed share
prices in the index higher, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
"There was some very good buying from local institutions
today," said Peter Struk of Reynolds &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed up 11.1 points at 2,666.2, off
its low of 2,640.2.
</P>
<P>
The stock averages, however, finished mixed, with the all
resources index closing down 15.2 points at 1,122.9 and the all
industrials closing up 40.1 points at 4,596.2.
</P>
<P>
Metal prices in London overnight did not help the resources
sector, with copper, aluminum and zinc prices tumbling to fresh
lows over concern on the Japanese economy and the slowing metals
demand in Asia.
</P>
<P>
National turnover remained thin, with 276.81 million shares
exchanged valued at 542.75 million U.S. dollars, and falls
outnumbered rises 658 to 514.
</P>
<P>
ANZ, which closed up 20 cents at 9.74 Australian dollars,
revealed it would slash its Australian workforce by a further
1,700 full-time positions to accelerate cost savings and steer
more customers towards electronic banking.
</P>
<P>
Struk said that the ANZ job losses would have "a big effect on
its bottom line" and raised speculation that the other banks would
also continue to cut staff to reduce costs to remain competitive.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank closed up 23.5 cents at 20.085
Australian dollars, Commonwealth Bank of Australia gained 18.2
cents to close at 17.73 Australian dollars and Westpac Banking
Corp. gained 5.9 cents to 10.10 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Major resource stocks finished mixed, with resources giant BHP
losing 36.7 cents, or 2.54 percent, to 14.083 Australian dollars,
and Rio Tinto gaining four cents to 18.59 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed down 14.7 points at 1,037.4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
