<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 08:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Technion Provides Video Self-service for Absent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 24 (Xinhua) -- At Technion, Israeli
Institute of Technology, students who missed classes for all
reasons now don not have to get worried anymore thanks to a
newly-dedicated video self-service.
</P>
<P>
The absent student needs only to insert his student card
into either of two videomat machines to get a video cassette
of the missed class and watch it either in his dorm or in
the library.
</P>
<P>
Earlier the week, Technion, which is based in the northern
port city Haifa, dedicated the self-service, computerized lending
facility in its multimedia library. The facility has a
collection of 1,000 cassettes.
</P>
<P>
The videomat machines are believed to be the only ones on
an Israeli campus, and perhaps the first in the world. The
student does not have to prove that being in the army,
illness or laziness was reason for absence, but merely pays a
fee of less than one U.S. dollar for each videotape.
</P>
<P>
The institute's spokesman Amir Zmora said there was some
hesitation about supplying the video films, since it could
encourage lazy students to stay away from classes.
</P>
<P>
But the administration finally decided that the benefit
surpassed the possible shortcomings, and that students who wanted
to participate actively in class by asking questions would not
be satisfied with seeing filmed lectures.
</P>
<P>
The videos, which were made of basic lectures, but not of
the more advanced courses, also will help students review
material that they heard live from their professors.
</P>
<P>
The video library has filmed lecturers in 32 different
courses, and students had already borrowed the cassettes for
thousands of times even before the automated machines were
installed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
