<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Success to Angola's Peace Process Doubted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Roberto de Almeida, speaker of
the Angolan National Assembly, reportedly said in Cuba Tuesday
that the recent series of incidents in Angola have raised doubts
among people over the successful ending to the country's peace
process.
</P>
<P>
He believed that it is impossible to complete all the tasks,
including the disbanding of all the remanent soldiers of the
former rebel UNITA (National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola), the re-establishment of national authority in
all UNITA-occupied regions, and the transforming of UNITA radio
station into commercial one before February 28, the prescribed
date set for the ending of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Higino Carneiro, spokesman for the Angolan government in the
Joint Commission of Angolan Peace Process, Monday also expressed
worries over the current political and military situation in the
country, which he said, is quite similar to that at the
end of 1992 when the civil war re-started.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the incidents of re-planting landmines,
armed attacks at local government and police headquarters and
killing innocent citizens in Luanda-Norte and Lunda-Sui Provinces in
the northeast, and central plateau and western cost, are
committed by the remanent UNITA soldiers and are all
organized and planned.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government has called on the joint commission
to take up necessary measures to prevent similar incidents
from ever happening again, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Carneiro said, the government has urged U.N.
observers in Angola to reinforce its strength in the areas
involved and send investigation teams to regions with serious
incidents reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
