<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar inched
higher Tuesday in Sydney in quiet dealing and traders said the
market was waiting for direction.
</P>
<P>
The unit closed at 66.62 U.S. cents, from 66.45 at the previous
session close.
</P>
<P>
Traders noted good two-way flows on the day, with buyers
lurking at 66.4 U.S. cents and sellers lined up around 66.8 U.S.
cents.
</P>
<P>
"It seems to be stuck in the middle of that" band, said Stuart
Moore, foreign exchange manager with St. George Bank Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the market was waiting for further directional
cues after the currency lost more than one U.S. cent during the
previous local session.
</P>
<P>
Those losses were driven by a softer Japanese yen against the
U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
But with the U.S. dollar/yen rate trading quietly Tuesday, the
Australian dollar could only follow suit.
</P>
<P>
Separately, U.S. investment house Merrill Lynch has said the
Australian dollar is now "deeply undervalued," following its
almost 20- percent collapse since late 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The Australian dollar is now the most undervalued of the
world's major currencies," Merrill Lynch said in a research
publication distributed to clients.
</P>
<P>
The currency fell to a 12-year low of 63.19 U.S. cents on
January 12.
</P>
<P>
Merrill Lynch said its fair value estimate for the local unit
is around 75 U.S. cents by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
"We expect the Australian dollar to appreciate significantly in
(the fiscal year of) 1998/99, returning at least to our fair value
level of 75 U.S. cents," it said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended in Sydney at 85.39 Japanese yen,
from 85.62 previously, and at 1.1968 Deutsche marks, from 1.2126.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
