<HEADLINE> China's Major Switchboard Manufacturer Enters GSM Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Great Dragon
Telecommunications (GDT), China's largest domestic switchboard
maker, has signed a framework cooperation agreement with DSC
Communications Corp. of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The agreement marks the entry of the two companies into China's
GSM market.
</P>
<P>
According to the pact, GDT and DSC will sell GSM systems in the
low-subscriber-density markets in China. The financial terms have
not been released.
</P>
<P>
In addition, they have been authorized by China United
Telecommunications (Unicom) to conduct a network trial on the
system.
</P>
<P>
Unicom is the second-largest telecommunications operator in
China, with GSM services covering more than 100 large and
medium-sized cities.
</P>
<P>
As foreign investors are barred from the market for value-added
telecom services, they hope to open up this field by exporting
equipment to China.
</P>
<P>
GDT is a group corporation consisting of eight large
state-owned enterprises. So far, it has supplied 6,000 switching
systems and 12 million subscriber lines to the country's Public
Switched Telephone Network.
</P>
<P>
The current production capacity of switching systems exceeds
the demand, industry analysts say, and GDT's cooperation with a
global provider of advanced telecom products will facilitate its
efforts to diversify its business and further involve itself in
mobile telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
According to China's Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications,
the country is the third-largest mobile telecom market in the
world. It had 13 million mobile telecom users at the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
An industry forecast says that China will become the largest
GSM market in the world by the year 2002, with 40 million GSM
users.
</P>
<P>
DSC had a revenue of 1.6 billion U.S. dollars in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
