<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian President Cancels Meeting With Donors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba has cancelled a meeting between his government and donors
sheduled to be held in London this week, Zambia's leading
independent newspaper The Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted diplomatic sources in Lusaka as saying Monday
that the meeting, an initiative of the Zambian government, was
intended to provide it an opporunity to persusade donors to
release 160 million U.S.Dollars in external financial assistance
for its 1998 budget.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba called off the meeting after it became clear that it
would yield no results due to continued reluctance among donors
to commit themselves to financial assistance until there is a
normalisaiton of the country's political situation, said the
sources.
</P>
<P>
"Ambasssadors of all the donor countries indicated they would
not attend such a meeting until there was progress on political
issues in the country," said a diplomatic source.
</P>
<P>
"And this is why President Chiluba is now trying to charge all
the coup detainees," the source stated.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba, according to the diplomatic sources, had a sheduled
pre-Paris Club meeting in London this week in the hope of
softening the donors stance ahead of the meeting of the Paris
Club scheduled tentatively for the end of march or april.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's 1998 budget envisages external support of at least
160 million dollars for this fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
However, the country's foiled military coup in October last
year, on-going state of emergency and the subsequent arrests of
coup suspects have tarnished Zambia's image and the donors'
confidence in its political stability.
</P>
<P>
The donors has urged Zambia to try as soon as possible the
detainees that include former president and opposition leader
Kenneth Kaunda. Last week the Zambian government said that the
coup suspects would face trial in "a few days".  
</P>
</TEXT>
