<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 08:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Increase Number of Palestinian Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Israel is creating a new
program to significantly reduce the number of foreign workers and
replace them with Palestinian workers, a local newspaper reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post said the government intends to cut the
number of foreign workers from 10 percent of the workforce to
under 1 percent by 2003. Israeli workforce currently totals some
2.054 million, according to the Central Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Yigal Ben Shalom, director-general of the Labor and Social
Affairs Ministry, was quoted as saying that as a major part of the
program, the ministry has cut the number of legal foreign workers
in the construction sector from 74,000 to 50,000 in 1997, and will
reduce it by a further 10,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the government will increase the number of
Palestinian workers from 70,000 to 80,000 this year. It is
estimated that each day about 30,000 Palestinian workers are
entering Israel to work legally, and another 30,000 coming in
illegally.
</P>
<P>
Gershon Baskin, director of the Jerusalem-based Israel and
Palestine Center for Research and Information, welcomed the
government decision.
</P>
<P>
He said that while some 62,000 permits have been issued to
Palestinians, about 50 percent of them could not find job in
Israel due to the large number of foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
But Ben-Shalom said that government is facing a big problem to
deal with a large number of illegal foreign workers in the
country, which is estimated at about 150,000. He said his
ministry has asked Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to increase
the number of monthly deportation of illegal foreign workers from
500 to 1,000.
</P>
<P>
Israeli leaders believe that the increased number of legal or
illegal foreign workers will create a huge social burden or
increase crimes. Palestinian workers, who don't reside in the
country, will not cause similar problems.
</P>
<P>
But until now, Israeli government seems to have not found a
viable way to accommodate the large number of Palestinian workers,
because terror attacks often forced Israel to impose closure on
the territories and ban the entry of Palestinian workers.
</P>
<P>
Yaccov Orr, Israeli Coordinator of Government Activities in
the Territories, said recently that Israel has begun allowing a
limited number of Palestinian workers to stay overnight during
times of closure. But these workers should go through strict
security checks before being issued such special permits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
