<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Airport Officials Foil Rare Animal Smuggling Attempt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Guangzhou Baiyun Airport
in south China's Guangdong Province recently confiscated 87 black
bear paws and 28 pangolins (scaly anteaters).
</P>
<P>
On Feb. 21, security officers at the airport detected a foul
odor coming from a crate which arrived there aboard South China
Airline Flight 4403 from Xishuangbanna in southwest China's Yunnan
Province. The airport security officers opened the crate and found
87 black bear paws and 28 pangolins, 19 living and nine dead. The
box weighed 300 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Bear paws and pangolin were once regarded as rare delicacies
and were formerly used in traditional Chinese medicine. However,
the two species are now under national protection and anyone found
killing the animals faces severe punishment.
</P>
<P>
Two people, a man and a woman, were taken into custody when
they were claiming the crate and the case is under investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
