<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, February 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Canada will not call back its troops in the Gulf
immediately despite an Iraqi deal brokered by United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Prime Minister Jean Chretien said
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We will stay to see if the implementation of the agreement is
really on course and respected by Saddam Hussein," Chretien
said. "We will call back our troops in due course after
consultation with our allies." (Canada-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic met United
States envoy Robert Gelbard Monday to exchange views on the
implementation of the Dayton agreement and other issues regarding
the peace process in the region.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have agreed that the Bosnian Serb government is
making an effort to improve economic and political conditions. The
stable operation of the government is important to the nation's
unity and economic development. Both of them maintained that
further enhancement of bilateral relations between Yugoslavia and
the United State would be beneficial to the common interests of
the two countries, and help strengthen the peace process and
stability of the region. (Yugoslavia-Gelbard)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan thanked
Italy on Monday for supporting his mission in Baghdad, said a
communique issued by the Italian premier's office.
</P>
<P>
The communique said Italian Premier Romano Prodi and Annan were
in constant contact during the U.N. chief's stay in the Iraqi
capital since Friday. Prodi expressed his confidence that the
agreement, which Annan will deliver to the U.N. Security Council
Tuesday, will ensure full and firm respect for U.N. resolutions
and mark the end of the Iraqi crisis. (Italy-Annan-Iraq Deal)
</P>
</TEXT>
