<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Welcomes Iraq-UN Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos said
Tuesday that the Philippines welcomes the agreement reached Monday
between the United Nations and Iraq to resolve the crisis over
U.N. weapons inspections in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"We join the international community in congratulating U.N.
Secretary General Kofi Annan and his team for the breakthrough
reached with Iraq during the secretary general's mission to Iraq,"
Ramos said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
But he also said the Philippines will continue to closely
monitor the situation in the area to ensure the safety and welfare
of the country's half a million overseas workers and their
dependents in the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Foreign Affairs has been asked to draw up a
contingency plan for the evacuation of the overseas workers in the
event that a military confrontation would erupt in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting earlier in the day with visiting Iraqi
Industry and Minerals Minister Adnan Abdul Majeed, Ramos also
reiterated his hope that the U.N.-Iraq agreement would reduce
tension in the region.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said he also hoped that the signing of the accord and its
final approval by the U.N. Security Council would pave the way for
U.N. weapons inspectors to resume their task and fulfill their
U.N. mandate.
</P>
<P>
Ramos congratulated Iraqi President Saddam Hussein for heeding
the call of the international community in ending the crisis
through diplomacy by fully cooperating with the U.N. chief and
avoiding further escalation of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Ramos also called on Iraq to fully comply with all relevant
U.N. Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Majeed, whose visit here was essentially to promote
Philippine-Iraqi trade relations, also sought the support of the
Philippines to their call for a lifting of the U.N. economic
embargo on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Majeed said Iraq was ready to cooperate with the international
community in solving the problem through diplomacy and without
resorting to force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
