<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urged to Quicken Grain Distribution Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- China should explore ways to
reform its grain distribution system as part of the country's bid
to establish a socialist market economy, today's Economic Daily
has urged.
</P>
<P>
Three years of successive bumper harvests have brought about
ample grain supply, stable grain prices and all-time high state
grain reserves, thus creating favorable conditions for reforming
the grain distribution system, notes a signed article in the
influential newspaper.
</P>
<P>
China's grain output is estimated to hit 490 million tons in
1997 in spite of rampant natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
Citing the fact that, in advanced countries, contract
agriculture has been highly effective in ensuring a stable market,
the report urges China follow suit and make grain production areas
and grain consumption areas sign three-year contracts that spell
out such items as the variety, quantity, quality, price, supply
date, ways of transaction and places of storage of grain.
</P>
<P>
The article also argued against the extremes of drastic hikes
and freezes in grain prices, both of which China has used to
stablize the market, and suggested "fine tuning" to protect both
producers and consumers.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper pointed to a rising contradiction between the
variety of grain and demand, saying that the country will face a
pressing demand for a structural change in grain production.
</P>
<P>
"When rural and urban residents have had enough to feed and
cloth themselves, they will start demanding quality of
consumption," says the article.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper also suggests that China enforce protective
policies to encourage farmers to grow grain varieties in short
supply. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
