<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 111 Centenarians Live in Northwest China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The number of centenarians in
northwest China's Shaanxi Province has increased from 72 in 1992
to 111 by the end of last year, according to the latest statistics
compiled by the provincial committee for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
The oldest is 108 and lives in a village in southern Shaanxi
Province.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that female centenarians outnumber males,
accounting for 71 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that 79 centenarians, or 71.2 percent,
live in the countryside, with 32 living in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Experts on the provincial committee for the elderly said that
most of the centenarians are cheerful and vegetarians, and live in
an uncontaminated environment.
</P>
<P>
Heredity was cited as one factor. More than 75 percent of the
centenarians' parents also lived long lives.
</P>
<P>
Experts also attributed the increasing number of centenarians
to an improved living standard. From last July, the centenarians
in the province began to receive a monthly 100-yuan pension from
related departments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 11 Rare Deer Found in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Eleven "David's deer," a rare
animal under national protection, have been found in Huarong
County in central China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
The deers were found eating vegetable by a local farmer in his
fields on Feb. 11. Having never seen such animals, the farmer and
his neighbors caught two.
</P>
<P>
David's deer has the antlers of a deer, the head of a horse,
and the body of a cow. The animal was named after Pere David, a
French Catholic priest and naturalist who first recorded the
existence of the unique deer in China in 1865.
</P>
<P>
David's deer was native to China until the early years of the
20th century, when Westerners invaded China and took the remaining
deers from an imperial park.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, the Marquess of Tavistock of England sent 20 of the
rare animals to Beijing, because of cooperation between the
Chinese and British governments.
</P>
<P>
The deers are now being raised in Beijing as well as Jiangsu
and Hubei provinces. Experts said the newly found deers are
probably from nearby Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
Related departments have put the two trapped deers under
special protection and required the county not to harm the
others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
