<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Supports UN-Iraq Accord over Inspections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi has said Iran fully supports the agreement reached
between the United Nations and Iraq on solving the arms inspection
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported Tuesday that Kharrazi
stated Iran has always believed in defusing the crisis through
diplomatic efforts.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the United Nations Security Council
would welcome the terms of the agreement resulting from U.N. chief
Kofi Annan's intense diplomacy in Baghdad to find a peaceful
solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Annan signed the deal with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq
Aziz Monday morning, which reportedly allows "immediate,
unfettered and unrestricted inspection" of all suspected sites in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain have threatened military
strike to force Iraqi compliance with the U.N. resolutions and
opening of presidential to U.N. inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said Annan's diplomatic efforts would not only help
enhance the creditability of the United Nations, but also open a
new golden leaf in the art of diplomacy replacing the gun
diplomacy for settlement of international disputes.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need for implementation of the U.N.
resolutions by Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
