<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysians Urged to Innovate Home-grown Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad Tuesday Urged local companies to possess the
capability to innovate home-grown technology in order to
manufacture products for local and foreign consumption.
</P>
<P>
In light of the current economic setbacks, local companies
should be smart to be self-reliant while at the same time cutting
overhead costs, Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when opening the MASTER Center, which
promotes greater automation in industries through the use of
robotics. The center is located in the Malaysian Technological
Park in Bukit Jalil here.
</P>
<P>
"Importing technologies and materials for our needs should be
minimized although that may be the easy way out," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said Malaysians should be bold in inventing products
and methods which others have not yet attempted to do.
</P>
<P>
"Let us not be too constrained by existing products invented by
others. Have confidence in ourselves," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the government would always accord due attention
to ventures geared towards self-production of goods.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysians should have full confidence in their
nation's ability to invent and produce goods of world standard
matching foreign-made ones.
</P>
<P>
He urged all parties to make the most of the robotics
facilities available at the Malaysian Technological Park for
purposes of training in components manufacturing and product
research development.
</P>
<P>
He said local companies should act fast in mastering foreign
technology and start producing components rather than merely
assembling those which are mostly imported.
</P>
<P>
Components manufacturing would require maintaining sizable
volume and international quality standards and should not be
limited to catering for local factories only but also for export.
</P>
<P>
He said as for providing services, Malaysia could also
capitalize on its position to offer consultancy services to
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"In making the most of the lower value of our currency now,
Malaysia, for instance, can provide services in information
technology at competitive terms," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
