<HEADLINE> Tornado-Hit Central Florida Declared Disaster Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. federal government
Monday declared a state of "major disaster" in central Florida,
making emergency aid available to victims of the tornados that
struck the region early in the day.
</P>
<P>
The White House said the declaration covers five counties in
central Florida already eligible for federal aid from storms on
Christmas Day, and adds 11 central Florida counties struck by
storms earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
The White House also said that President Bill Clinton expressed
his concern about the safety and welfare of the victim families
and will go the Florida on Wednesday to view the tornado damage.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the president has sent representatives of the Federal
Emergency Management Agency (FEMA), including FEMA director James
Lee Witt, to the tornado-struck area.
</P>
<P>
El Nino-driven tornadoes ripped across central Florida early
Monday, killing at least 38 people, injuring more than 250 others
and leading to 10 more missing.
</P>
<P>
The tornadoes, struck the region from Daytona Beach on the
Atlantic Coast and to the Tampa Bay area on the Gulf Coast, with
some wind speeds as high as 210 mph (336 kph), also destroyed
hundreds of houses and knocked out power for more than 135,000
residents in the region.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-three people were killed in Osceola County and 11 others
were confirmed dead near Sanford in Seminole County about 20 miles
northeast of Orlando. Three were killed in Orange County and one
in Volusia County.
</P>
<P>
In Osceola County southeast of Orlando, emergency officials
said about 200 houses and other structures were damaged or
destroyed and in Orange County, about 100 mobile houses were
damaged or destroyed.
</P>
<P>
The storm was caused partially by the wind patterns and
conditions directed by El Nino, weather service officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Pacific warm-water phenomenon is blamed for a number of
unusual weather patterns around the world, including the series of
storms in California that have caused an estimated 475 million
U.S. dollars in damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
