<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria to Reduce Armed Forces by One Third before 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria is to cut down the
number of its troops from the present 104,000 to 75,000 by the
year 2000, a major step in the military reform, national
newspapers reported here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mikho Mikhov, chief of General Staff of the Bulgarian armed
forces, was quoted as telling reporters Sunday that the force
reduction will be a "natural process" in which a soldier's term of
service will be shortened from one and a half years to one year,
and the number of military college recruits will be gradually
reduced.
</P>
<P>
During the reform, army officers will determine themselves
whether they will remain in the army or retire, Mikhov added.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that the ongoing military reform is aimed at
reducing the quantity and improving the quality of the armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
The reform comprises three stages, the first of which was
already completed in 1997 with the withdrawal of troops stationed
in six defended zones.
</P>
<P>
The major tasks in the second stage from 1998 to 2000 are
troop reduction, military restructuring and the establishment of
a rapid reaction force.
</P>
<P>
In the third stage from 2001 to 2010, Bulgaria will set up
professional armed forces and achieve military modernization to a
level close or parallel to the standards of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
Last July at NATO's special summit in Madrid, Poland, Hungary
and the Czech Republic were invited to join NATO in the first
wave. The three countries will become NATO members in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria ranks fourth among the Balkan countries with regard to
the number of armed forces. With 640,000 troops, Turkey ranks
first, followed by Romania and Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
