<HEADLINE> French Friends Recall Chinese Premier Zhou Enlai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 23 (Xinhua) -- French officials, diplomats,
sinologists and members of Sino-French friendship associations met
here Monday to mark the centennial of the birth of the late
Chinese Premier, Zhou Enlai.
</P>
<P>
The mayor of the 13th Arrondisement of Paris, Jacques Toubon,
laid a spray of flowers before the Number 17 Hotel on the Rue
Godefroy, where Zhou once lived in the early 1920s during his time
in France.
</P>
<P>
The house, which has a green bronze plaque on its wall with a
relief of Zhou, and his name personally written by Deng Xiaoping,
has become a place of pilgrimmage for Chinese visitors.
</P>
<P>
At the memorial meeting in the city hall of the 13th
Arrondisement, French Academician and sinologist Alain Peyreffite
recalled the three meetings he had with Zhou in Beijing in the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
Zhou, who died on January 8, 1976, once told him that during
his stay in France, the hospitality of the French people and their
good feelings toward foreigners had left him with a deep
impression, said Peyreffite.
</P>
<P>
He said that Zhou always supported a strong and united Europe
to counter hegemony by the superpowers, and backed the
independent foreign policy of France under General Charles De
Gaulle.
</P>
<P>
Former delegate minister of the French Foreign Ministry Andre
Bettencourt recalled his meetings with Zhou and Deng Xiaoping in
Beijing in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
He said Deng once told him that it was in France that both he
and Zhou found the only way to save China was by Revolution.
</P>
<P>
Bettencourt said a common fate led Zhou and Deng to fight
together all their life for a strong and prosperous China.
</P>
<P>
The secretary general of the Franco-Chinese Friendship
Association, Madame Marchisio, said that when she was teaching
French at the Foreign Affairs College in Beijing in the 1960s and
70s, Premier Zhou personally cared about her work.
</P>
<P>
Former French ambassador to China Challe Malo and former French
military attache in Beijing General Henri Eyraud also memorized
their personal friendship with Premier Zhou. 
</P>
</TEXT>
