<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Forecast 5.4 percent growth in Venezuela
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- The Union of Swiss Banks forecasts that Venezuela
will register an economic growth of 5.4 at the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Predictions of the "El Nacional" journal are that the inflation
rate would be 30 percent, the international reserves would be 11
billion dollars and a devaluation of 8.9 percent would occur.
</P>
<P>
Argentineans have high sugar consumption
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentineans have doubled the world average
sugar consumption, and sugar prices there are among the lowest
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
A published report by the Argentinean Sugar Center says each
person consumes an average of 40 Kilograms of sugar a year. The
world average is 21 Kilograms.
</P>
<P>
The report said the sugar price was 0.62 peso (62 U.S. cents) a
kilogram, one of the lowest compared with countries with a high
per capita income. Sugar in Japan costs 2 dollars per kilogram,
and in France 1.35 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Chile's Fruit Exports to U.S. Fall
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's fruit and vegetable exports to the United
States decreased by 7.5 percent this season compared to the
previous one.
</P>
<P>
The Association of Exporters said 30,187,000 boxes were shipped
until February 15. The figure in the same period of last year was
32,641,000 boxes.
</P>
<P>
Nicaraguan Dockyard will export ships to Central America
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- The Vermar dockyard at Puerto Corinto, in Nicaragua,
announced that it would export fishing ships to Guatemala, El
Salvador, Honduras and Costa Rica this year.
</P>
<P>
Minimum wage buys more meat in Brazil
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The monthly minimum wage in Brazil, around 120
dollars, can buy 42 kilograms of bovine meat today, an increase of
61.5 percent over the 26 kilograms in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Mexico Shows Deficit on Running Account
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The running account of the Mexican balance of
payments had a deficit of 7.315 billion U.S. dollars in 1997,
equal to 1.8 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP) said the
Bank of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Contributed revenues increase in Costa Rica
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Contributed revenues in Costa Rica last month
totalled 126.35 million dollars, an increase of 11 percent against
the amount in the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Treasury Ministry figures show that from the total, customs tax
totalled 61.36 million dollars, an increase of 10 percent over
last year, and Federal income tax totalled 30.48 million dollars,
26 percent more.
</P>
<P>
The data shows that revenues from sales tax was only 13.17
million dollars, a decrease of 31 percent against the 19.85
million dollars in January 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
