<HEADLINE> Thailand Urges Australia to Open Chicken Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has asked
Australia to open its market to Thai frozen boiled chicken.
</P>
<P>
The request was made when Thai Agriculture Minister Pongpol
Adireksarn met with Australian Ambassador William Fisher here
Monday to discuss trade and agricultural cooperation between the
two countries, according to the newspaper Bangkok Post Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Pongpol proposed that the Australian government
open the country's market for Thai frozen boiled chicken which has
been prohibited in line with the country's sanitary standard.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Fisher asked the Thai government to import more
skimmed milk from Australia.
</P>
<P>
Thailand was also urged to consider reducing its import duty on
fruit such as cherries, strawberries and apples.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed agricultural cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Pongpol was quoted as saying Thailand is interested in
technical and livestock promotion cooperation while Australia
emphasized agricultural trade and investment cooperation.
</P>
