<HEADLINE> Thailand Expects $62.6 Billion Exports in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bangkok, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has set the target
for exports in 1998 at 62.6 billion U.S. dollars, up 7.1 percent
from last year, the Nation newspaper said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
To promote Thai exports to meet the target, the Council of
Economic Ministers met on Monday and ordered the implementation of
six measures to solve the liquidity problems faced by exporters.
</P>
<P>
The six measures include bank recapitalization by June this
year, reduction of reserves on risk assets for exporters' credit,
increase of packing credits, facilitation of automobile exports,
tax rebates and fighting sea pirates.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Finance Ministry announced the trade figures for
1997, saying the country's exports value reached 58.4 billion
dollars, up by 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also reported that Thailand in January recorded a
trade surplus for the fifth consecutive month, but exports in the
month declined from December.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the 1997 rise of exports to the
depreciation of the baht and a fall in imports due to reduced
domestic purchasing power.  
</P>
</TEXT>
