<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Takes up Campaign Finance Debate Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Legislators advocating an
overhaul of the country's current campaign finance system resumed
their efforts in the Senate Monday, but conceded they lack the 60
votes to overcome a Republican-led filibuster.
</P>
<P>
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, a Republican, made clear he
will not permit the major bill to linger long on the floor.
</P>
<P>
The bipartisan measure, drafted by Republican Senator John
McCain and Democratic Senator Russ Feingold, would ban unregulated
"soft money" to national political parties from corporations,
labor unions and individuals.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it would impose new restrictions on advertisements
that attack candidates but escape regulation because they are
presented as "issue ads" not covered by existing election law.
</P>
<P>
Most Republicans, led by Lott, have countered with a proposal
that would require organized labor to obtain the consent of
members before using their union dues on political advocacy.
</P>
<P>
The McCain-Feingold proposal is not likely to garner the 60
votes needed to overcome a filibuster and force Lott and other
opponents to the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
The fight may eventually lead to a compromise bill by Senator
Olympia Snowe, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
She and other Republican moderates have put forward a proposal
requiring speedy disclosure of contributors to any broadcast
commercials targeting specific candidates within 30 days of a
primary or 60 days of a general election.
</P>
<P>
It would also prohibit the use of union or corporate funds for
such ads.
</P>
<P>
It would "simply require funding to come from sources
traditionally relied upon for campaign purposes -- PACs (political
action committees) or individual, voluntary donors," a summary of
the legislation said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethnic Regional Autonomy System Ensures Political Rights of Tibetans (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The implementation of the
ethnic regional autonomy system has further guaranteed the
political rights of the Tibetan people, said a white paper
released by the Information Office of China's State Council here
today.
</P>
<P>
Entitled "New Progress in Human Rights in the Tibet Autonomous
Region", the white paper said that Tibet is an area where the
Tibetans live in compact communities, with people of the Tibetan
ethnic group making up 95 percent of the total population of 2.44
million in the autonomous region, and the people of the Han and
other ethnic groups accounting for only five percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the Constitution of the People's Republic of
China, the state practices the ethnic regional autonomy system in
Tibet, which has been established as the Tibet Autonomous Region,
and safeguards, according to law, the political rights of the
people of all ethnic groups in Tibet to participate in
administration of state and local affairs on an equal basis,
especially the Tibetan people's autonomous right to independently
administer local and ethnic affairs.
</P>
<P>
In April 1956, the Preparatory Committee for the Tibet
Autonomous Region was set up in accordance with the Central
Government's decision, the white paper said.
</P>
<P>
The Tibet Autonomous Region was formally founded in 1965, with
Ngapoi Ngawang Jigme as the first chairman of the Region. As the
organs of self-government, the Tibet Autonomous Regional People's
Congress and the Regional People's Government exercise the power
of autonomy according to law.
</P>
<P>
The white paper said that the Tibet Autonomous Regional
People's Congress and its Standing Committee -- the local organs
of state power in Tibet -- fully exercise the power of autonomy
bestowed by the Constitution and law, and have actively formulated
laws and regulations appropriate to local ethnic and regional
characteristics.
</P>
<P>
Between 1965 and 1992 more than 60 local laws and regulations
were worked out, such as the Rules of Procedure of the People's
Congress of the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethnic Regional Autonomy System Ensures Political Rights of Tibetans (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In recent years the Region has formulated 23 local laws and
regulations, made 21 legal decisions, and cleared up or revised 23
laws and regulations involving politics, the economy, culture,
education, environmental protection and other fields. In addition,
rules for the implementation of 14 national laws and regulations
conforming to the local features of Tibet have been drawn up.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, the number of laws and regulations
worked out since 1992 by the People's Congress of the Tibet
Autonomous Region and its Standing Committee to safeguard the
interests of the Tibetan people in light of the actual conditions
in Tibet exceeds the total formulated during the 12 years
preceding 1992.
</P>
<P>
The chairman of the Standing Committee of the Tibet Autonomous
Regional People's Congress and the chairman of the Tibet Autonomous
Region are both citizens of the Tibetan ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
Since the founding of the Tibet Autonomous Region all the four
chairmen of the Standing Committee of the People's Congress of
the Tibet Autonomous Region and five chairmen of the Region have
been Tibetan citizens.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Tibetan and other ethnic minorities now account
for 71.4 percent of the chairman and vice-chairmen of the Standing
Committee of the People's Congress of the Tibet Autonomous Region;
for 80 percent of the members of the Standing Committee of the
Autonomous Regional People's Congress; and for 77.8 percent of the
chairman and vice-chairmen of the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Further progress has been made in the training and selection of
cadres of Tibetan and other ethnic minorities in Tibet since
1992. According to 1996 statistics, the number of cadres belonging
to the Tibetan and other ethnic minorities in Tibet had increased
by 18.22 percent over the 1992 figure, making up 73.88 percent of
the total and showing an increase of 4.48 percentage points over
the figure for 1992.
</P>
<P>
The white paper said that guaranteeing the study and use of the
Tibetan language is an important aspect of safeguarding the
Tibetan people's right to autonomy and exercising their right to
participate in the administration of state and local affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
