<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Loans Help to Improve Rural Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- More than four million people
in 40 poverty-ridden rural counties of four provinces and the
Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region will be provided with piped-in
water by 2001, when a WB-funded water improvement project is
scheduled for completion.
</P>
<P>
The 1.1 billion yuan (132 million U.S. dollars) project will
build pumping stations, install pipes and taps for each household,
according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Pilot work on other renovations will match up in each of the
counties, which includes improved sanitation facilities in schools
and the spreading of publicity and education programs related to
water and environmental sanitation problems.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has promised to provide a loan of 70 million
U.S. dollars for the five-year project, which started at the
end of 1997 and designed to benefit 4.6 million citizens in
more than 3,000 villages in Hebei, Jiangxi, Hubei and Yunnan
provinces as well as Inner Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
China started cooperation with the World Bank in upgrading
rural water in 1985, according to Liu Jiayi, division chief in
charge of rural water improvement with the National Patriotic
Health Campaign Commission.
</P>
<P>
Since then and through 2001, loans totalling about 300 million
U.S. dollars have be used and will flow to support 140 counties to
improve water, which will benefit 21 million people.
</P>
<P>
China has also established collaborations with seven
international organizations and governments of some foreign
countries.
</P>
<P>
The quality of drinking water in rural areas has greatly
improved, with more than 86 percent of the rural residents now get
tap water, compared with less than 10 percent in the early 1980s,
according to figures from the Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the commission say the national target of
providing 90 percent of the rural population with drinkable water
by the end of the century can be achieved.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980224.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Shares Open Higher </HEADLINE>
