<HEADLINE> Trade Sanction Against Iraq May Be lifted: French Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, February 23 (Xinhua) -- French Defense Minister Alain
Richard said here Monday that if Iraq would not hinder the work of
U.N. weapons inspectors, trade sanctions against that country
could be lifted.
</P>
<P>
Richard made the remark at a joint press conference after his
talks with his Hungarian counterpart Gyorgy Keleti.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that France considers a diplomatic solution to the
Iraqi crisis of major importance. As a permanent member of the
U.N. Security Council, France will carefully study the agreement
reached between U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan and Iraqi
leaders.
</P>
<P>
He said the five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council
will further coordinate their stand on this issue after studying
the content of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Hungarian Defense Minister Keleti said although the U.N. and
Baghdad reached an agreement, the Hungarian medical team is still
ready to go to the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
The two defense ministers signed a secret treaty on Monday to
exchange military technology and materials.
</P>
<P>
Richard also met Monday with the Hungarian president, prime
minister and foreign minister to exchange views on bilateral
relations and the eastward expansion of NATO (North Atlantic
Treaty Organization). He expressed France's support to Hungary's
entrance into NATO and promised to provide assistance to Hungary
on military training and education.
</P>
<P>
Richard was on a one-day official visit to Hungary at the
invitation of the Hungarian defence minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
