<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar, US Jointly Survey Opium Yield in Shan State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar and the United States
jointly surveyed illicit poppy plantations and collected poppy
samples in Myanmar's northeastern Shan State during the last week,
the official New Light of Myanmar newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, the fourth under a joint anti-drug program of the
two governments, was carried out by a team comprising personnel of
the state-run Myanmar Agricultural Service and the U.S. Department
of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The areas under survey covered Pinlaung, Leicha, Mongpan,
Siseng, Loilem, Mongmaw, Wa, Hopang and Tangyang, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted one and a half months after Myanmar
launched a three-month nationwide campaign in January to collect
baseline data on opium cultivation and drug addicts in the
country. The move was initiated due to a wide gap in the estimates
of the area and production of opium by Myanmar and the United
States, according to the authorities.
</P>
<P>
The two countries undertook similar surveys in other areas in
Shan State in 1993, 1995 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to an earlier official report, the Myanmar
authorities destroyed more than 16,000 hectares of illicit poppy
plantations in 17 townships of Shan State between last November
and this January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
