<HEADLINE> Thailand Continues to Seek Economic Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will continue talks
with economic superpowers to seek assistance to restructure its
economy and guarantee exports, according to Thai Foreign Minister
Surin Pitsuwan.
</P>
<P>
The country will stress its need for economic assistance at
several forums including the Asia-Europe Meeting and the
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Post Tuesday quoted Surin as saying the Thai
government has sought help from developed countries in
guaranteeing letters of credit for Thai exporters. To date, the
Group of Seven (G-7) industrialized countries have not taken any
concrete actions to assist Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Exporters need to import materials for production and
manufacturing. Cooperation from the developed countries will help
Thai exporters fill their orders, thus boosting the economy, Surin
said.
</P>
<P>
Negotiating the rollover of short-term foreign debts held by
the private sector is another urgent task for the Thai government,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Surin said Thailand has received firm support from the German,
Dutch and British governments, which said they would urge banks to
assist Thai firms.
</P>
<P>
Surin also welcomed last week's decision by G-7 finance
ministers to help shore up confidence in Asian economies.
</P>
</TEXT>
