<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Aids African Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- China is planning to launch two
more agricultural projects in African countries this year
following a successful one in Guinea, said today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Republic of the Congo and Cote d'Ivoire will
cooperate with China to bolster their agricultural development, a
Ministry of Agriculture official was quoted as saying in this
Beijing-based newspaper.
</P>
<P>
These two projects will follow the rule applied by the program
in Guinea.
</P>
<P>
China planted rice in 9,000 hectares of land in Guinea last
year. The rice yield in the project area reached six tons per ha.
</P>
<P>
The planting area will be expanded to 18,000 hectares this
year. China also plans to diversify its investment in Guinea by
setting up a feed lot to raise 200,000 table hens and a 500-sq.m
reservoir available to raise fish.
</P>
<P>
The Guinea project is scheduled to involve three phases of
construction. China is projected to pour 18.16 million US dollars
into the first phase which will be completed by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The project will increase the production capacity of rice in
Guinea by 400,000 tons a year after its completion.
</P>
<P>
The cooperated project also provided training for local farmers
who will eventually increase their incomes by applying new
technology.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
