<HEADLINE> Fighter Aircraft to See $100 Billion Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 23 (Xinhua) -- A total of 3,369
fighter/attack/jet trainer aircraft valued at 100.8 billion U.S.
dollars will be produced worldwide in the next ten years, a U.S.
company forecast.
</P>
<P>
The annual output will be on the rise during the second
five-year period, according to the Connecticut-based Forecast
International/DMS.
</P>
<P>
Company analysts said the immediate post-Cold War environment
coupled with a major economic recession resulted in
across-the-board force reductions by all but a few nations, with
other countries postponing modernization plans.
</P>
<P>
Several countries are now addressing procurement which have
been on the shelf for the past few years, they said in a report
released on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The primary market motivator, however, is a major re-equipment
cycle beginning to shape up in the United States and western
Europe," the report noted.
</P>
<P>
"This will result in large-scale acquisitions of Dassault
Rafales by France, of EF 2000s by the Eurofighter member nations
and in the U.S., of Boeing F/A-18E/Fs, Lockheed F-22s and the
USAF/USN Joint Strike Fighter (JSF)," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Forecast International is a leading provider of market
intelligence services for the aerospace, defense, power systems,
and transportation industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
