<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Cautiously Endorses Annan's Deal with Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Monday cautiously endorsed a tentative agreement between
Secretary General of the United Nations Kofi Annan and Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein which carries a promise from Baghdad to
allow U.N. weapons inspectors full access to presidential sites in
Iraq for searching weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
"I hope today's agreement will prove to be the step forward
that we had been looking for," Clinton told an Oval Office news
conference.
</P>
<P>
But he said some issues still needed to be clarified and
details to be spelled out.
</P>
<P>
"There are issues that still need to be clarified to our
satisfaction and details that need to be spelled out," he said.
"We will hear from the U.N. secretary-general tomorrow on
these questions, and we will work with him and with UNSCOM (U.N.
Special Commission) to make sure the inspections are rigorous
and professional."
</P>
<P>
Clinton made the remarks after he and Vice President Al Gore
were briefed by National Security Adviser Sandy Berger on what the
administration knows about the tentative agreement.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, meanwhile, was briefed
by Bill Richardson, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, who
had a copy of the agreed document.
</P>
<P>
Before the news conference, Clinton had a lengthy discussion
with British Prime Minister Tony Blair, and he planned to call
Russian President Boris Yeltsin and French President jacques
Chirac. Clinton also spoke with Annan on sunday night after
Annan struck the agreement with Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
He said Saddam Hussein had for the first time since the 1991
Gulf War promised unfettered access to his presidential areas.
</P>
<P>
But Clinton said whether Saddam allows weapons inspectors
unlimited access to his presidential sites remains "a big if."
</P>
<P>
"The proof is in the testing," he stressed. "We have to
monitor Iraq's compliance with the commitment it made at the end
of the Gulf War to give up all of its biological, chemical, and
nuclear weapons, the missiles to deliver them and the capacity
to rebuild its arsenal."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said there will be serious consequences if Iraq once
again fails to allow complete inspections of suspected weapons
sites.
</P>
<P>
"If Iraq fails to comply this time to provide immediate,
unrestricted, unconditional access to the weapons inspectors,
there will be serious consequences," he said
</P>
<P>
He said if Iraq doesn't keep its word this time, everyone in
the United States and its allies would recognize that the United
States has the "unilateral right to respond." And the United
States will keep its forces in the Gulf for military action once
Saddam breaks his words by his deeds.
</P>
<P>
"I intend to keep our forces at high levels of preparation in
the Gulf in the near term to see what happens in terms of
honoring these obligations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Senator Majority Leader Trent Lott said Clinton may be "in a
box" -- stuck with the tentative agreement he has to accept.
</P>
<P>
"I was worried that this initiative by Annan was going to put
the president in a box and that's exactly what's happened," Lott
told reporters at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
"This is another example of how the administration's foreign
policy is subcontracted to others ... Everybody says this is
good enough,and yet it may not be good enough," he said. "But
the president would be in such a box because of the way it was
handled he had no alternative." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
