<HEADLINE> UK Prime Minister Calls for New UN Resolution on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 23 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair said Monday that United Nations Secretary-General Kofi
Annan's deal with Iraq should be backed up with a new Security
Council resolution to ensure that Iraq comply with the accord
completely.
</P>
<P>
"It is absolutely essential that we are not back in this
position in a few weeks or a few months' time," Blair told
reporters outside his Downing Street office.
</P>
<P>
Blair made the statement after a long telephone conversation
with U.S. President Bill Clinton. He said that he wanted to be
sure the crisis would not happen again and there would be no
repetition of the "long-drawn-out diplomatic game" with Iraq's
President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Blair added that Britain has to check the fine print of the
agreement, saying that if the deal brokered by Annan delivered
"unconditional, unrestricted, immediate access to these so-called
presidential sites" then that would be "precisely what we have
been arguing for".
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday, a Downing Street spokesman said that Britain
had told its U.N. ambassador Michael Weston to step up work on a
new Security Council resolution which would give authority for the
U.N. to respond "rapidly and by whatever means are necessary"
should Saddam break the agreement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
