<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tornadoes Kill More Than 30 People in Florida </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 23 (Xinhua) -- El Nino-driven tornadoes
ripped across central Florida early Monday, killing at least 33
people and destroying hundreds of homes and knocking out power for
thousands of residents in the region.
</P>
<P>
Tornadoes were reported from Daytona Beach on the Atlantic
Coast to the Tampa Bay area on the Gulf Coast, with some having
had wind speeds as high as 210 mph (336 kph).
</P>
<P>
Eighteen people were killed in Osceola County and 11 others
were confirmed dead near Sanford in Seminole County about 20 miles
northeast of Orlando. Three were killed in Orange County and one
in Volusia County.
</P>
<P>
Most of the deaths were scattered through three or four
neighborhoods in counties around the Orlando region.
</P>
<P>
Two other people were unaccounted for near Lake Harney, just
northeast of Orlando.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports estimated the death toll to as many as 43.
</P>
<P>
The tornadoes uprooted trees and cut electrical poles, leaving
more than 135,000 people in central Florida without power.
</P>
<P>
In Seminole County just northeast of Orlando, roofs ripped from
homes scattered in the fields and shiny sheet metal from mobile
homes hung high in trees. Some cars were crushed by fallen trees.
</P>
<P>
In Osceola County southeast of Orlando, emergency officials
said about 200 houses and other structures were damaged or
destroyed and in Orange County, about 100 mobile homes were
damaged or destroyed.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton said Monday that he was sending
representatives of the Federal Emergency Management Agency,
including FEMA director James Lee Witt, to the tornado area.
</P>
<P>
The storm was caused partially by the wind patterns and
conditions directed by El Nino, weather service officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Pacific warm-water phenomenon is blamed for a number of
unusual weather patterns around the world, including the series of
storms in California that have caused an estimated 475 million
U.S. dollars in damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
