<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Reduces NATO Expansion Cost Estimate to $1.5 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States Monday
reduced its estimate of the cost of bringing Poland, Hungary and
the Czech Republic to the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) to 1.5 billion U.S. dollars over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
"This reflects more recent and more complete information than
the Department's February 1997... cost figures of 4.9 billion U.S.
dollars to 6.2 billion U.S. dollars," said the Pentagon in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The estimate parallels a NATO estimate in November, which said
it would cost 1.5 billion U.S. dollars over 10 years to let the
new three invitees join.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. cost will be "the standard U.S. share of about 25
percent," said the statement, released at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon's new estimate came as the administration planned
to send Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Defense
Secretary William Cohen to Capitol Hill to argue Tuesday for the
NATO expansion before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
NATO leaders decided to accept the three nations by 1999 and
the decision needs to be approved by the Senate with a vote of
two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
Lawmakers have cited the various cost estimates as part of
their concern over whether to approve the alliance's enlargement.
The Senate is to vote on it next month.
</P>
<P>
Critics pointed out that the Clinton administration
intentionally reduced the estimated cost of the expansion so as to
gain a quick ratification. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
